{"title_page": "Sharon Ann Hunt", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Sharon Ann Hunt\n| honorific_suffix = Professor\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = American\n| citizenship = \n| education = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = \n| relations = \n| website = \n| profession = [[Cardiologist]]\n| field = [[Heart transplant]]\n| work_institutions = \n| specialism = \n| research_field = [[Organ rejection]]\n| notable_works = \n| prizes = * 2012, ISHLT Lifetime achievement award \n*2013, Hewlett award \n| child = daughter\n| module2 = \n| signature = \n}}\n'''Sharon Ann Hunt''' is a cardiology professor and Director of the Post Heart Transplant Programme in [[Palo Alto, California]] and is affiliated with [[Stanford University Medical Center]], professionally known for her work in the care of patients after [[heart transplantation]].\n\nWith a career at Stanford spanning over fifty years, Hunt has witnessed the history of heart transplant surgery from the very first one in the US by [[Norman Shumway]] in 1968, through the international moratorium on heart transplants and the recent decades of [[heart-lung transplant|combined heart-lung transplants]] and [[left ventricular assist device|mechanical assist devices]].\n\nShe is a past president of the [[International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation]] and received their lifetime achievement award in 2012.\n\nAs one of the 130 cardiology specialists at Stanford, her other activities include contributions to [[Uptodate]] and ''Hurst's Cardiology'' and more than 200 publications.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSharon Ann Hunt was brought up in [[Cleveland, Ohio]] and completed her early education from the undergraduate school at the [[University of Dayton]].  She spent her summer breaks in a research laboratory at the Cleveland Clinic, sparking her interest in cardiology and subsequent entry to the study of medicine.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.practiceupdate.com/author/sharon-hunt/403|title=Sharon Hunt|website=PracticeUpdate|language=en|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe began her medical career as a one of seven female students in her class at Stanford in 1967, the year prior to the landmark heart transplant procedure by [[Norman Shumway]].<ref name=\"Stanford2013\">{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.stanford.edu/news/current-news/hewlett-awards/sharon-hunt-hewlett-award.html|title=Cardiologist Sharon Hunt to Receive Hewlett Award|website=Department of Medicine<br>News|language=en|access-date=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs a medical student, she became involved in research observing the effects of several drugs on [[Cardiac muscle cell|heart muscle cells]] in tissue culture, a project that introduced her to many of the cardiac trainees at Stanford at that time.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\"/>\n\n==Medical career==\nHunt received a medical degree in 1972, completed a [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in internal medicine in 1974, and finished a cardiology fellowship in 1977, all at [[Stanford University]]. She achieved internal medicine certification by the [[American Board of Internal Medicine]] in 1977 and their cardiovascular disease certification in 1979.<ref name=StanfordBio>{{cite web| url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/sharon-hunt |title=Sharon Hunt, M.D. | publisher=Stanford University Medical Center }}</ref>\n\nShe was mentored by heart translant pioneer Norman Shumway and pathologist [[Margaret Billingham]] and also worked with cardiothoracic surgeon [[Philip Caves]] and [[Edward Stinson (surgeon)|Edward Stinson]], and has therefore witnessed the history of heart transplant surgery in the US from its early years.<ref name=Stanford2013/><ref name=ishltinterview2011>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/about-ishlt/ishlt-history-project/video-interviews|title=Video interview with Sharon Ann Hunt|last=Ross|first=Heather|date=November 2011|website=ww.ishlt.org|access-date=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===First heart transplant, 1968===\nAs a second-year medical student, she has recounted the first heart transplant procedure in the US as \"groundbreaking...very exciting\" when \"the whole place was abuzz with the news of it\".<ref name=abc7news>{{Cite news|url=https://abc7news.com/health/stanford-marks-50-years-since-first-us-adult-heart-transplant-performed-there/2863207/|title=Stanford marks 50 years since first U.S. adult heart transplant performed there|last=|first=|date=5 January 2018|work=ABC7 San Francisco|access-date=3 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> She recalls the poor survival rates and the vast public interest which led members of the press to climb the outside of the hospital to try to get pictures inside the hospital.<ref name=abc7news/>\n\n===Organ rejection===\nDuring the late 1970s, as Hunt was completing her training, the one-year survival rates for heart transplant surgery was around 60%. Post-operative care of heart transplant patients, with long-term [[immunosuppression]], was a new and evolving field with as yet unknown complications and problems. Over the previous decade, surgical techniques, including endomyocardial biopsy use for early transplant rejection, were improved at Stanford, under Norman Shumway.<ref name=Stanford2013/> The care of people who had survived the initial stages of heart transplant surgery became the focus of Hunt's research and work. Continuing the work in the recognising of and the treating of rejection, she also looked at methods in lessening drug side effects.<ref name=\"Stanford2013\" /><ref name=StanfordBio/>\nShe later recalled; <blockquote>When patients started living longer, the surgeons felt they needed real doctors to take care of them because they would come in for follow up with all sorts of medical complications of long-term immunosuppression.<ref name=Stanford2013/> </blockquote>\n\nContinuing the process, which started in 1973, of monitoring acute rejection after heart transplants by taking biopsies of the heart using a [[bioptome]] and then examining the samples under the microscope, has in her professional view been one of the most significant contributions to detecting rejection.<ref name=\"npr50\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/01/06/576197731/marking-50-years-since-the-first-american-heart-transplant|title=Marking 50 Years Since The First Adult Heart Transplant In The U.S.|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHunt is known by a number of her colleagues as the \"mother of transplant\",<ref name=ishltinterview2011/> having been involved in major transplant guidelines including the \"2009 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Heart Failure in Adults\u201d.<ref name=ishltinterview2011/>\n\nIn her paper on mechanical circulatory support in 2007, she stated that the grading of \u201ctransplant ineligible\u201d at one moment in time is not automatically a permanent decision.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oA3iDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1 McKellar, Shelley (2017), p.153]</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Hunt described one-year survival rates of 90% with many living for over thirty years.<ref name=Stanford2013/>\n\n===Mechanical assist devices===\nHunt was involved in the care of Robert St. Laurent, the case of the world's first successful implantation of an LVAD, as a [[bridge to transplantation]], in 1984.<ref name=ishltinterview2011/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2004/april14/transplant.html|title=Heart transplant reunion party celebrates lifesaving milestone|website=news.stanford.edu|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> The device used was the \u201cNovacor\u201d (left ventricular assist system), which used an electromechanically driven dual pusher-plate blood pump. Later, the Thoratec HeartMate XVE device became approved with the landmark REMATCH trial.<ref name=\"JoyceJoyce2011\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Mi2fuanLfQC&pg=PA3|title=Mechanical Circulatory Support: Principles and Applications|author1=Nos\u00e9|first=Yukhiko|last2=Motomra|first2=Tadashi|date=2011|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-178507-5|editor-last=Joyce|editor-first=David L.|location=|pages=3|chapter=History of mechanical Circulatory Support|editor-last2=Joyce|editor-first2=Lyle D.|editor-last3=Locke|editor-first3=Matthias}}</ref>\n\nHunt wrote the commentary on the REMATCH trial, \"Randomized Evaluation of Mechanical Assistance for the Treatment of Congestive Heart Failure\", a trial led by [[Eric Rose (surgeon)|Eric A. Rose]].<ref name=\"REMATCH2002\"/> This trial intended to assess the suitability of using a LVAD in the long-term in people with end-stage (severe) heart failure who were not suitable for heart transplantation. Just under 130 people with at least three months of ([[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|class IV]]) [[congestive heart failure]], despite maximum tolerated treatment with drugs and who were ineligible for heart transplantation, were recruited and assigned to either fitting with an LVAD or treatment with medicines only, and all co-ordinated by a specialist co-ordination centre. Despite frequent complications of [[sepsis|infection]], [[thrombosis]], [[cerebrovascular disease]], device malfunction and one [[left ventricular dysfunction]] in the LVAD group, they [LVAD group] had a significantly improved survival rate to those that received medication only and where deaths were due to mostly left ventricular dysfunction. Scores on [[quality of life]] depended on the questionnaires used.<ref name=\"LandmarkREMATCH2002\">{{Cite journal|last=Hunt|first=Sharon A.|date=April 2002|title=Comment--the REMATCH trial: Long-term use of a left ventricular assist device for end-stage heart failure|journal=Journal of Cardiac Failure|volume=8|issue=2|pages=59\u201360|issn=1071-9164|pmid=12016626|doi=10.1054/jcaf.2002.32944}}</ref><ref name=\"McKellar,Shelley(2017)\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oA3iDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|title=Technological Change in Modern Surgery: Historical Perspectives on Innovation|last=McKellar|first=Shelley|publisher=University of Rochester Press|year=2017|isbn=978-1-58046-594-6|editor=Schlich|editor-first=Thomas|location=|pages=129\u2013138|chapter=Disruptive Potential: The \u201cLandmark\u201d REMATCH Trial, Left Ventricular Assist Device (LVAD) Technology, and the Surgical Treatment of Heart Failure in the United States|editor2-last=Crenner|editor2-first=Christopher}}</ref>\n\nAlthough using LVADs as an artificial heart in order to buy time and bridge the gap until a heart transplant was initially for short-term means, some people have kept them for long periods of time and some have been able to wean off the device to recovery.<ref name=\"LandmarkREMATCH2002\"/>\n\nDuring that presentation at the American Heart Association 2002 annual meeting, Hunt made it clear that she believed that the REMATCH trial symbolised a basis \"for all future trials of mechanical heart replacement.\u201d<ref name=\"REMATCH2002\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.acc.org/latest-in-cardiology/clinical-trials/2010/02/23/19/16/rematch|title=Randomized Evaluation of Mechanical Assistance for the Treatment of Congestive Heart Failure - American College of Cardiology|website=American College of Cardiology|access-date=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Appointments===\nHer career subsequently evolved at Stanford and she progressed as clinical instructor and assistant, associate professor and then eventually clinical professor in 1993, becoming professor in the Division of Cardiovascular Medicine.<ref name=Stanford2013/>\n\nShe is one of the 130 cardiology specialists at Stanford.<ref name=SHProfile>{{Cite news|url=https://health.usnews.com/doctors/sharon-hunt-23832|title=Dr Sharon Hunt, Cardiology Profile|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2010 she became board certified in advanced heart failure and transplant cardiology. Heart transplants are a focus of her practice.<ref name=StanfordBio/>\n\n===Organisations===\nHunt succeeded [[John Wallwork (surgeon)|John Wallwork]] in 1995 to serve as president of the International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation from 1995-1996.<ref name=Presidents>{{cite web|title=ISHLT Past Presidents|url=http://www.ishlt.org/boardsAndCommittees/pastPresidents.asp|publisher=The International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ISHLTawardHunt2012\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/grants-awards/lifetime-achievement/2012-recipient|title=ISHLT: The International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation - 2012 Lifetime Achievement Award Recipient|website=www.ishlt.org|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> She was succeeded by William Baumgartner.<ref name=Presidents/>\n\nShe is a [[American College of Cardiology|Master of the American College of Cardiology]].<ref name=ACC>{{cite web|title=2014 Distinguished Awardees|url=http://www.acc.org/membership/member-benefits-and-resources/award-programs/acc-distinguished-awards-program/2014%20distinguished%20awardees|publisher=[[American College of Cardiology]]|accessdate=April 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410143114/http://www.acc.org/membership/member-benefits-and-resources/award-programs/acc-distinguished-awards-program/2014%20distinguished%20awardees|archivedate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe works with [[UpToDate]] and Hurst\u2019s ''The Heart''.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\"/>\n\n==Awards and achievements==\nOn 19 April 2012, at the ISHLT 32nd Annual Meeting and Scientific Sessions in Prague, Czech Republic.,<ref name=ISHLTawardHunt2012/> she was awarded the ISHLT Lifetime achievement award,<ref name=Stanford2013/> the fifth recipient of that award.<ref name=Lifetime>{{cite web|title=Lifetime Achievement Award|url=http://www.ishlt.org/awards/lifetimeAchievement.asp|publisher=International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation |accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref> A year later, she received the Hewlett award.<ref name=Stanford2013/>\n\nShe has published more than 200 peer-reviewed articles.<ref name=Stanford2013/> In 2014, the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] included Hunt in its ISI Highly Cited database, which lists scientists whose publications have been most often cited by other researchers.<ref name=ISI>{{cite web|title=Highly Cited Researchers|url=http://highlycited.com/archive_december_2014.htm|publisher=[[Institute for Scientific Information]]|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe has chaired joint committees of the American College of Cardiology and [[American Heart Association]] which have revised patient care guidelines for heart failure.<ref name=Circulation>{{cite journal|title=ACC/AHA 2005 Guideline Update for the Diagnosis and Management of Chronic Heart Failure in the Adult|journal=[[Circulation (journal)|Circulation]]|date=2005|issue=12|pages=e154\u2013e235|doi=10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.105.167586|pmid=16160202|volume=112|vauthors=Hunt SA, Abraham WT, Chin MH |display-authors=etal|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Personal and family==\nHunt married a psychologist. He died in 2004.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\"/> She has one daughter who is a police officer in [[Sacramento]].<ref name=\"Stanford2013\"/>\n\nClose to home, some of her time is spent with horses, growing orchids and traveling. \u201cOne of the privileges of what I\u2019ve done over the years is the opportunity to travel all over the world as an honoured guest\u201d.<ref name=\"Stanford2013\"/>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n===Books===\n*Associate editor in [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lx7DQzdASfAC&q=sharon+ann+hunt+heart&dq=sharon+ann+hunt+heart&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibuJjLzJvdAhWkJsAKHShYDjoQ6AEITzAJ ''Hurst's the Heart''], published by McGraw Hill Professional, 2011, {{ISBN|9780071636483}}.\n\n===Papers===\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.healun.2017.10.007 | volume=36 | title=Conquering the first hurdles in cardiac transplantation: In the footprints of giants | year=2017 | journal=The Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation | pages=1276\u20131278 | author=Hess Michael L., Hunt Sharon}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(83)92867-2 | volume=321 | title=COMBINED HEART AND LUNG TRANSPLANTATION | year=1983 | journal=The Lancet | pages=1130\u20131132 | author=Jamieson StuartW, Reitz BruceA, Oyer PhilipE, Billingham Margaret, Modry Dennis, Baldwin John, Stinson EdwardB, Hunt Sharon, Theodore James, Bieber CharlesP, Shumway NormanE}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 9229305 | volume=16 | title=Pulmonary hypertension in severe congestive heart failure: how important is it? | year=1997 | author=Hunt SA | journal=J Heart Lung Transplant | pages=S13-5 }}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 9392531 | doi=10.1016/s0360-3016(97)00504-x | volume=39 | title=Long-term results of total lymphoid irradiation in the treatment of cardiac allograft rejection | year=1997 | author=Wolden SL, Tate DJ, Hunt SA, Strober S, Hoppe RT | journal=Int J Radiat Oncol Biol Phys | pages=953\u201360 }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0022-5223(99)70375-2 | volume=117 | title=Thirty years of cardiac transplantation at stanford university | year=1999 | journal=The Journal of Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery | pages=939\u2013951 | author=Robbins Robert C., Barlow Clifford W., Oyer Philip E., Hunt Sharon A., Miller Joan L., Reitz Bruce A., Stinson Edward B., Shumway Norman E.}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S1053-2498(01)00258-3 | volume=20 | title=Severe tricuspid regurgitation after heart transplantation | year=2001 | journal=The Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation | pages=709\u2013717 | author=Chan Michael C.Y, Giannetti Nadia, Kato Tomoko, Kornbluth Murray, Oyer Phil, Valantine Hannah A, Robbins Robert C, Hunt Sharon A}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid =  11486285 | doi=10.1086/322733 | volume=33 | title=Infectious complications among 620 consecutive heart transplant patients at Stanford University Medical Center | year=2001 | author=Montoya JG, Giraldo LF, Efron B, Stinson EB, Gamberg P, Hunt S, Giannetti N, Miller J, Remington JS | journal=Clin Infect Dis | pages=629\u201340 }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.107.715300 | volume=116 | title=Mechanical Circulatory Support | year=2007 | journal=Circulation | pages=461\u2013462 | author=Hunt Sharon A}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1054/jcaf.2002.32944 | pmid=12016626 | volume=8 | title=Comment--the REMATCH trial: Long-term use of a left ventricular assist device for end-stage heart failure | year=2002 | author=Hunt SA | journal=J Card Fail | pages=59\u201360}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.jacc.2008.05.020 | url = https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82642959.pdf | volume=52 | title=The Changing Face of Heart Transplantation | year=2008 | journal=Journal of the American College of Cardiology | pages=587\u2013598 | author=Hunt Sharon A., Haddad Fran\u00e7ois }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.112.111948 | volume=125 | title=A Bridge Far Enough? | year=2012 | journal=Circulation | pages=3069\u20133072 | author=Warner Stevenson Lynne, Hunt Sharon A}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 23953556 | doi = 10.1016/j.transproceed.2013.01.106 | volume=45 | title=Granulocyte colony-stimulating factor therapy is associated with a reduced incidence of acute rejection episodes or allograft vasculopathy in heart transplant recipients | year=2013 | author=Vrtovec B, Haddad F, Pham M, Deuse T, Fearon WF, Schrepfer S, Leon S, Vu T, Valantine H, Hunt SA | journal=Transplant Proc | pages=2406\u20139}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 23498821| doi = 10.1016/j.transproceed.2012.08.02 | volume=45 | title=ST-elevation myocardial infarction following heart transplantation as an unusual presentation of coronary allograft vasculopathy: a case report | year=2013 | author=Peter S, Hulme O, Deuse T, Vrtovec B, Fearon WF, Hunt S, Haddad F | journal=Transplant Proc | pages=787\u201391}}\n\n===Guidelines===\n*{{cite journal | pmid =  19324966 | doi=10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.109.192065 | volume=119 | title=2009 focused update incorporated into the ACC/AHA 2005 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Heart Failure in Adults: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines: developed in collaboration with the International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation | date=April 2009 | author=Hunt SA, Abraham WT, Chin MH | display-authors = etal | journal=Circulation | pages=e391\u2013479 }}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunt, Sharon Ann}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Stanford Medical School alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Sharon Ann Hunt\n| honorific_suffix = Professor\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = American\n| citizenship = \n| education = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = \n| relations = \n| website = \n| profession = [[Cardiologist]]\n| field = [[Heart transplant]]\n| work_institutions = \n| specialism = \n| research_field = [[Organ rejection]]\n| notable_works = \n| prizes = * 2012, ISHLT Lifetime achievement award \n*2013, Hewlett award \n| child = daughter\n| module2 = \n| signature = \n}}\n'''Sharon Ann Hunt''' is a cardiology professor and Director of the Post Heart Transplant Programme in [[Palo Alto, California]] and is affiliated with [[Stanford University Medical Center]], professionally known for her work in the care of patients after [[heart transplantation]].\n\nWith a career at Stanford spanning over fifty years, Hunt has witnessed the history of heart transplant surgery from the very first one in the US by [[Norman Shumway]] in 1968, through the international moratorium on heart transplants and the recent decades of [[heart-lung transplant|combined heart-lung transplants]] and [[left ventricular assist device|mechanical assist devices]].\n\nShe is a past president of the [[International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation]] and received their lifetime achievement award in 2012.\n\nAs one of the 130 cardiology specialists at Stanford, her other activities include contributions to [[Uptodate]] and ''Hurst's Cardiology'' and more than 200 publications.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSharon Ann Hunt was brought up in [[Cleveland, Ohio]] and completed her early education from the undergraduate school at the [[University of Dayton]].  She spent her summer breaks in a research laboratory at the Cleveland Clinic, sparking her interest in cardiology and subsequent entry to the study of medicine.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.practiceupdate.com/author/sharon-hunt/403|title=Sharon Hunt|website=PracticeUpdate|language=en|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe began her medical career as a one of seven female students in her class at Stanford in 1967, the year prior to the landmark heart transplant procedure by [[Norman Shumway]].<ref name=\"Stanford2013\">{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.stanford.edu/news/current-news/hewlett-awards/sharon-hunt-hewlett-award.html|title=Cardiologist Sharon Hunt to Receive Hewlett Award|website=Department of Medicine<br>News|language=en|access-date=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs a medical student, she became involved in research observing the effects of several drugs on [[Cardiac muscle cell|heart muscle cells]] in tissue culture, a project that introduced her to many of the cardiac trainees at Stanford at that time.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\"/>\n\n==Medical career==\nHunt received a medical degree in 1972, completed a [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in internal medicine in 1974, and finished a cardiology fellowship in 1977, all at [[Stanford University]]. She achieved internal medicine certification by the [[American Board of Internal Medicine]] in 1977 and their cardiovascular disease certification in 1979.<ref name=StanfordBio>{{cite web| url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/sharon-hunt |title=Sharon Hunt, M.D. | publisher=Stanford University Medical Center }}</ref>\n\nShe was mentored by heart translant pioneer Norman Shumway and pathologist [[Margaret Billingham]] and also worked with cardiothoracic surgeon [[Philip Caves]] and [[Edward Stinson (surgeon)|Edward Stinson]], and has therefore witnessed the history of heart transplant surgery in the US from its early years.<ref name=Stanford2013/><ref name=ishltinterview2011>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/about-ishlt/ishlt-history-project/video-interviews|title=Video interview with Sharon Ann Hunt|last=Ross|first=Heather|date=November 2011|website=ww.ishlt.org|access-date=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===First heart transplant, 1968===\nAs a second-year medical student, she has recounted the first heart transplant procedure in the US as \"groundbreaking...very exciting\" when \"the whole place was abuzz with the news of it\".<ref name=abc7news>{{Cite news|url=https://abc7news.com/health/stanford-marks-50-years-since-first-us-adult-heart-transplant-performed-there/2863207/|title=Stanford marks 50 years since first U.S. adult heart transplant performed there|last=|first=|date=5 January 2018|work=ABC7 San Francisco|access-date=3 September 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> She recalls the poor survival rates and the vast public interest which led members of the press to climb the outside of the hospital to try to get pictures inside the hospital.<ref name=abc7news/>\n\n===Organ rejection===\nDuring the late 1970s, as Hunt was completing her training, the one-year survival rates for heart transplant surgery was around 60%. Post-operative care of heart transplant patients, with long-term [[immunosuppression]], was a new and evolving field with as yet unknown complications and problems. Over the previous decade, surgical techniques, including endomyocardial biopsy use for early transplant rejection, were improved at Stanford, under Norman Shumway.<ref name=Stanford2013/> The care of people who had survived the initial stages of heart transplant surgery became the focus of Hunt's research and work. Continuing the work in the recognising of and the treating of rejection, she also looked at methods in lessening drug side effects.<ref name=\"Stanford2013\" /><ref name=StanfordBio/>\nShe later recalled; <blockquote>When patients started living longer, the surgeons felt they needed real doctors to take care of them because they would come in for follow up with all sorts of medical complications of long-term immunosuppression.<ref name=Stanford2013/> </blockquote>\n\nContinuing the process, which started in 1973, of monitoring acute rejection after heart transplants by taking biopsies of the heart using a [[bioptome]] and then examining the samples under the microscope, has in her professional view been one of the most significant contributions to detecting rejection.<ref name=\"npr50\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/01/06/576197731/marking-50-years-since-the-first-american-heart-transplant|title=Marking 50 Years Since The First Adult Heart Transplant In The U.S.|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHunt is known by a number of her colleagues as the \"mother of transplant\",<ref name=ishltinterview2011/> having been involved in major transplant guidelines including the \"2009 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Heart Failure in Adults\u201d.<ref name=ishltinterview2011/>\n\nIn her paper on mechanical circulatory support in 2007, she stated that the grading of \u201ctransplant ineligible\u201d at one moment in time is not automatically a permanent decision.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oA3iDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1 McKellar, Shelley (2017), p.153]</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Hunt described one-year survival rates of 90% with many living for over thirty years.<ref name=Stanford2013/>\n\n===Mechanical assist devices===\nHunt was involved in the care of Robert St. Laurent, the case of the world's first successful implantation of an LVAD, as a [[bridge to transplantation]], in 1984.<ref name=ishltinterview2011/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2004/april14/transplant.html|title=Heart transplant reunion party celebrates lifesaving milestone|website=news.stanford.edu|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> The device used was the \u201cNovacor\u201d (left ventricular assist system), which used an electromechanically driven dual pusher-plate blood pump. Later, the Thoratec HeartMate XVE device became approved with the landmark REMATCH trial.<ref name=\"JoyceJoyce2011\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Mi2fuanLfQC&pg=PA3|title=Mechanical Circulatory Support: Principles and Applications|author1=Nos\u00e9|first=Yukhiko|last2=Motomra|first2=Tadashi|date=2011|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-178507-5|editor-last=Joyce|editor-first=David L.|location=|pages=3|chapter=History of mechanical Circulatory Support|editor-last2=Joyce|editor-first2=Lyle D.|editor-last3=Locke|editor-first3=Matthias}}</ref>\n\nHunt wrote the commentary on the REMATCH trial, \"Randomized Evaluation of Mechanical Assistance for the Treatment of Congestive Heart Failure\", a trial led by [[Eric Rose (surgeon)|Eric A. Rose]].<ref name=\"REMATCH2002\"/> This trial intended to assess the suitability of using a LVAD in the long-term in people with end-stage (severe) heart failure who were not suitable for heart transplantation. Just under 130 people with at least three months of ([[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|class IV]]) [[congestive heart failure]], despite maximum tolerated treatment with drugs and who were ineligible for heart transplantation, were recruited and assigned to either fitting with an LVAD or treatment with medicines only, and all co-ordinated by a specialist co-ordination centre. Despite frequent complications of [[sepsis|infection]], [[thrombosis]], [[cerebrovascular disease]], device malfunction and one [[left ventricular dysfunction]] in the LVAD group, they [LVAD group] had a significantly improved survival rate to those that received medication only and where deaths were due to mostly left ventricular dysfunction. Scores on [[quality of life]] depended on the questionnaires used.<ref name=\"LandmarkREMATCH2002\">{{Cite journal|last=Hunt|first=Sharon A.|date=April 2002|title=Comment--the REMATCH trial: Long-term use of a left ventricular assist device for end-stage heart failure|journal=Journal of Cardiac Failure|volume=8|issue=2|pages=59\u201360|issn=1071-9164|pmid=12016626|doi=10.1054/jcaf.2002.32944}}</ref><ref name=\"McKellar,Shelley(2017)\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oA3iDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|title=Technological Change in Modern Surgery: Historical Perspectives on Innovation|last=McKellar|first=Shelley|publisher=University of Rochester Press|year=2017|isbn=978-1-58046-594-6|editor=Schlich|editor-first=Thomas|location=|pages=129\u2013138|chapter=Disruptive Potential: The \u201cLandmark\u201d REMATCH Trial, Left Ventricular Assist Device (LVAD) Technology, and the Surgical Treatment of Heart Failure in the United States|editor2-last=Crenner|editor2-first=Christopher}}</ref>\n\nAlthough using LVADs as an artificial heart in order to buy time and bridge the gap until a heart transplant was initially for short-term means, some people have kept them for long periods of time and some have been able to wean off the device to recovery.<ref name=\"LandmarkREMATCH2002\"/>\n\nDuring that presentation at the American Heart Association 2002 annual meeting, Hunt made it clear that she believed that the REMATCH trial symbolised a basis \"for all future trials of mechanical heart replacement.\u201d<ref name=\"REMATCH2002\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.acc.org/latest-in-cardiology/clinical-trials/2010/02/23/19/16/rematch|title=Randomized Evaluation of Mechanical Assistance for the Treatment of Congestive Heart Failure - American College of Cardiology|website=American College of Cardiology|access-date=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Appointments===\nHer career subsequently evolved at Stanford and she progressed as clinical instructor and assistant, associate professor and then eventually clinical professor in 1993, becoming professor in the Division of Cardiovascular Medicine.<ref name=Stanford2013/>\n\nShe is one of the 130 cardiology specialists at Stanford.<ref name=SHProfile>{{Cite news|url=https://health.usnews.com/doctors/sharon-hunt-23832|title=Dr Sharon Hunt, Cardiology Profile|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2010 she became board certified in advanced heart failure and transplant cardiology. Heart transplants are a focus of her practice.<ref name=StanfordBio/>\n\n===Organisations===\nHunt succeeded [[John Wallwork (surgeon)|John Wallwork]] in 1995 to serve as president of the International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation from 1995-1996.<ref name=Presidents>{{cite web|title=ISHLT Past Presidents|url=http://www.ishlt.org/boardsAndCommittees/pastPresidents.asp|publisher=The International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ISHLTawardHunt2012\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/grants-awards/lifetime-achievement/2012-recipient|title=ISHLT: The International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation - 2012 Lifetime Achievement Award Recipient|website=www.ishlt.org|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref> She was succeeded by William Baumgartner.<ref name=Presidents/>\n\nShe is a [[American College of Cardiology|Master of the American College of Cardiology]].<ref name=ACC>{{cite web|title=2014 Distinguished Awardees|url=http://www.acc.org/membership/member-benefits-and-resources/award-programs/acc-distinguished-awards-program/2014%20distinguished%20awardees|publisher=[[American College of Cardiology]]|accessdate=April 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410143114/http://www.acc.org/membership/member-benefits-and-resources/award-programs/acc-distinguished-awards-program/2014%20distinguished%20awardees|archivedate=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe works with [[UpToDate]] and Hurst\u2019s ''The Heart''.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\"/>\n\n==Awards and achievements==\nOn 19 April 2012, at the ISHLT 32nd Annual Meeting and Scientific Sessions in Prague, Czech Republic.,<ref name=ISHLTawardHunt2012/> she was awarded the ISHLT Lifetime achievement award,<ref name=Stanford2013/> the fifth recipient of that award.<ref name=Lifetime>{{cite web|title=Lifetime Achievement Award|url=http://www.ishlt.org/awards/lifetimeAchievement.asp|publisher=International Society for Heart & Lung Transplantation |accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref> A year later, she received the Hewlett award.<ref name=Stanford2013/>\n\nShe has published more than 200 peer-reviewed articles.<ref name=Stanford2013/> In 2014, the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] included Hunt in its ISI Highly Cited database, which lists scientists whose publications have been most often cited by other researchers.<ref name=ISI>{{cite web|title=Highly Cited Researchers|url=http://highlycited.com/archive_december_2014.htm|publisher=[[Institute for Scientific Information]]|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe has chaired joint committees of the American College of Cardiology and [[American Heart Association]] which have revised patient care guidelines for heart failure.<ref name=Circulation>{{cite journal|title=ACC/AHA 2005 Guideline Update for the Diagnosis and Management of Chronic Heart Failure in the Adult|journal=[[Circulation (journal)|Circulation]]|date=2005|issue=12|pages=e154\u2013e235|doi=10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.105.167586|pmid=16160202|volume=112|vauthors=Hunt SA, Abraham WT, Chin MH |display-authors=etal|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Personal and family==\nHunt married a psychologist. He died in 2004.<ref name=\"PracticeUpdate\"/> She has one daughter who is a police officer in [[Sacramento]].<ref name=\"Stanford2013\"/>\n\nClose to home, some of her time is spent with horses, growing orchids and traveling. \u201cOne of the privileges of what I\u2019ve done over the years is the opportunity to travel all over the world as an honoured guest\u201d.<ref name=\"Stanford2013\"/>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n===Books===\n*Associate editor in [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lx7DQzdASfAC&q=sharon+ann+hunt+heart&dq=sharon+ann+hunt+heart&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibuJjLzJvdAhWkJsAKHShYDjoQ6AEITzAJ ''Hurst's the Heart''], published by McGraw Hill Professional, 2011, {{ISBN|9780071636483}}.\n\n===Papers===\n*[https://www.jhltonline.org/article/S1053-2498(17)32057-0/fulltext Conquering the first hurdles in cardiac transplantation: In the footprints of giants], co-authored with [[Michael L. Hess]], ''Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation'', 21 May 1983, {{DOI|10.1016/j.healun.2017.10.007}}, pp.&nbsp;1276\u20131278.\n*[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140673683928672/abstract Combined heart and lung transplantation], co-authored with Stuart W. Jamieson, Bruce Reitz, Philiip E. Oyer, Margaret Billingham, Dennis Modry, John Baldwin, Edward Stinson, James Theodore, Carles P. Bieber, Norman E. Sumway, ''[[The Lancet]]'', 21 May 1983, C{{DOI|10.1016/S0140-6736(83)92867-2}}, pp.&nbsp;1130\u20131132.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9229305 \"Pulmonary hypertension in severe congestive heart failure: How important is it?\"], ''Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation'', 16 June 1997, S13-S15 {{PMID|9229305}}.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9392531 \"Long-term results of total lymphoid irradiation in the treatment of cardiac allograft rejection\"], co-authored with  Wolden, S. L., Tate, D. J., Strober, S., Hoppe, R. T. ''International Journal of Radiation Oncology Biology Physics.'' 1 December 1997: pp.&nbsp;953\u2013960.\n*[https://www.jtcvs.org/article/S0022-5223(99)70375-2/fulltext \"Thirty years of cardiac transplantation at Stanford University\"], co-authored with [[Robert C. Robbins]], Clifford W. Barlow, [[Philip E. Oyer]], Joan L. Miller, [[Bruce Reitz|Bruce A. Reitz]], Edward B. Stinson, Norman E. Shumway, ''[[The Journal of Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery]]'', May 1999 Volume 117, Issue 5, {{DOI|10.1016/S0022-5223(99)70375-2}}, pp.&nbsp;939\u2013951.\n*[https://www.jhltonline.org/article/S1053-2498(01)00258-3/fulltext \"Severe [[tricuspid regurgitation]] after heart transplantation\"], co-authored with Chan MC, Giannetti N, Kato T, Kornbluth M, Oyer P, Valantine HA, Robbins RC, ''[[The Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation]]'', 20 July 2001, {{DOI|10.1016/S1053-2498(01)00258-3}}, pp.&nbsp;709\u201317.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11486285 \"Infectious complications among 620 consecutive heart transplant patients at Stanford University Medical Center Montoya\"], co-authored with J. G., Giraldo, L. F., Efron, B., Stinson, E. B., Gamberg, P., Hung, S., Giannetti, N., Miller, J., Remington, J. S. ''[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]]'', 1 September 2001, {{PMID|11486285}}, {{DOI|10.1086/322733}}, pp.&nbsp;629\u2013640.\n*[https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1161/circulationaha.107.715300 \u201c[[Mechanical Circulatory Support]], New Data, Old Problems\u201d], ''Circulation'' 31 July 2007, {{doi|10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.107.715300}}.\n*[https://www.onlinejcf.com/article/S1071-9164(02)80598-X/fulltext \"The REMATCH trial: Long-term use of a left ventricular assist device for end-stage heart failure for the Randomized Evaluation of Mechanical Assistance for the Treatment of Congestive Heart Failure (REMATCH) Study Group\"], co-authored with E.A. Rose, April 2002, {{DOI|10.1054/jcaf.2002.32944}}, pp.&nbsp;59\u201360.\n*[https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82642959.pdf  \u201cThe Changing Face of Heart Transplantation\u201d], co-authored with Fran\u00e7ois Haddad], ''Journal of the American College of Cardiology'', 2008 {{doi|10.1016/j.jacc.2008.05.020}}.\n*[https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.112.111948 \"A Bridge Far Enough\"], ''[[Circulation (journal)|Circulation]]'', 26 June 2012, {{doi|10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.112.111948}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23953556 \"Granulocyte Colony-Stimulating Factor Therapy Is Associated With a Reduced Incidence of Acute Rejection Episodes or Allograft Vasculopathy in Heart Transplant Recipients\"], co-authored with Vrtovec, B., Haddad, F., Pham, M., Deuse, T., Fearon, W. F., Schrepfer, S., Leon, S., Vu, T., Valantine, H.,''[[Transplantation Proceedings]]'', 2013, {{doi|10.1016/j.transproceed.2013.01.106}}, pp.&nbsp;2406\u20132409.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23498821 \"ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction Following Heart Transplantation as an Unusual Presentation of Coronary Allograft Vasculopathy: A Case Report\"], co-authored with Peter, S., Hulme, O., Deuse, T., Vrtovec, B., Fearon, W. F., Haddad, F. '' Transplantation Proceedings'', 2013, {{PMID|23498821}}, {{DOI|10.1016/j.transproceed.2012.08.02}}, pp.&nbsp;787\u2013791.\n\n===Guidelines===\n*[https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.109.192065 2009 \u201cFocused Update Incorporated Into the ACC/AHA 2005 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Heart Failure in Adults\u201d], \u201cA Report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines: Developed in Collaboration With the International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation,\u201d co-authored with William T. Abraham, Marshall H. Chin, Arthur M. Feldman, Gary S. Francis, Theodore G. Ganiats, Mariell Jessup, Marvin A. Konstam, Donna M. Mancini, Keith Michl, John A. Oates, Peter S. Rahko,, Marc A. Silver, Lynne Warner Stevenson, Clyde W. Yancy, Circulation, 30 March 2010, {{PMID|19324966}}, {{DOI|10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.109.192065}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunt, Sharon Ann}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Stanford Medical School alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharon_Ann_Hunt"}
{"title_page": "Nick Wiger", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedy writer, actor, and podcaster}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}{{notability|1=Biographies|date=April 2019}}}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nick Wiger\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = Nicolas Frank Wiger\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1980|08|28}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Comedian, writer, podcaster\n| years_active       = 2007&ndash;present\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = Burger Boy\n}}\n\n'''Nicolas Frank \u201cNick\u201d Wiger''' (born August 28, 1980) is an American comedian, improviser, podcast personality, and television writer. He is the co-founder and co-host (with actor and comedian [[Mike Mitchell (actor)|Mike Mitchell]]) of the popular weekly podcast [[Doughboys (podcast)|''Doughboys'']],<ref>https://headgum.com/doughboys</ref> which reviews chain restaurants with guests and includes additional segments centered around snack food and related topics. As of June 2019, he is also the co-host (with [[Heather Anne Campbell]]) of [[How Did This Get Played? (podcast)|''How Did This Get Played?'']],<ref>https://www.earwolf.com/show/how-did-this-get-played/</ref> a podcast about low-rated and weird video games.\n\nAs a television writer, Wiger's extensive career spans a wide range of work including the FOX sketch show ''[[Party Over Here]]'' (where he was head writer), Sarah Silverman's [[I Love You, America with Sarah Silverman|''I Love You, America'']], the long-running Comedy Central game show ''[[@midnight]]'', and the TV show version of [[Scott Aukerman]]'s [[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|''Comedy Bang! Bang!'']] <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4696339/</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWiger was raised in [[Long Beach]], [[California]] and is an alumnus of [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School]].\n\n==Career==\nWiger began his career as a video game tester and designer.<ref>https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,136235/</ref> After dropping out of college,{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} he began studying, performing, and teaching as an [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] and sketch comedian at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theater]] (UCB) in [[Los Angeles]]. He most notably was a member of the sketch and improv team A Kiss From Daddy, alongside comedians [[Paul Rust]], [[Eva Anderson]], [[Michael Blaiklock|Mookie Blaiklock]], [[Neil Campbell (producer)|Neil Campbell]], [[Michael Cassady]], [[Dave Horwitz]], [[Allan McLeod]], and [[Harris Wittels]].<ref>https://franklin.ucbtheatre.com/show/1915</ref>\n\n===''Doughboys''===\nWiger created the comedy podcast ''[[Doughboys (podcast)|Doughboys]]'' with comedy writer [[Mike Mitchell (actor)|Mike Mitchell]] in 2015. ''[[Doughboys (podcast)|Doughboys]]'' was named \"The One Food Podcast to Start With\" by pop culture site Vulture.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite news|last=Legaspi|first=Althea|title=The One Podcast to Start With, Across 24 Topics|pages=|publisher=Vulture|date=2015-10-05|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/one-podcast-to-start-with-across-24-topics.html|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref> The co-hosts review chain restaurants with a weekly guest, including [[Nicole Byer]], [[Haley Joel Osment]], [[Sarah Silverman]], among others.<ref>https://headgum.com/doughboys</ref> Wiger's fans call him the \"Burger Boy\" and refer to themselves as members of the \"Burger Brigade\".\n\nAs of early 2018, the podcast is no longer associated with [[Feral Audio]] and is now a member of the [[HeadGum]] network. Mitchell and Wiger use [[Patreon]] to bring exclusive paid ''Doughboys'' content to their subscribers beyond the weekly episodes. As of February 2020, the ''Doughboys'' Patreon is the 9th most popular podcast Patreon and the 27th most popular Patreon in general.<ref>https://graphtreon.com/creator/doughboys</ref>\n\n===''How Did This Get Played?''===\nSince June 2019, Wiger is also the co-host (with [[Heather Anne Campbell]]) of [[How Did This Get Played? (podcast)|''How Did This Get Played?'']], a podcast about \"the worst and weirdest\" video games.<ref>https://www.earwolf.com/show/how-did-this-get-played/</ref> The name is derived from fellow [[Earwolf]] podcast ''[[How Did This Get Made?]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|4696339}}\n*{{Instagram|nickwiger}}\n*{{Twitter|nickwiger}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiger, Nick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Upright Citizens Brigade Theater performers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American comedy writer, actor, and podcaster}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}{{notability|1=Biographies|date=April 2019}}}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nick Wiger\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = Nicolas Frank Wiger\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1980|08|28}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Comedian, writer, podcaster\n| years_active       = 2007&ndash;present\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = Burger Boy\n}}\n\n'''Nicolas Frank \u201cNick\u201d Wiger''' (born August 28, 1980) is an American comedian, improviser, podcast personality, and television writer. He is the co-founder and co-host (with actor and comedian [[Mike Mitchell (actor)|Mike Mitchell]]) of the popular weekly podcast [[Doughboys (podcast)|''Doughboys'']],<ref>https://headgum.com/doughboys</ref> which reviews chain restaurants with guests and includes additional segments centered around snack food and related topics. As of June 2019, he is also the co-host (with [[Heather Anne Campbell]]) of [[How Did This Get Played? (podcast)|''How Did This Get Played?'']],<ref>https://www.earwolf.com/show/how-did-this-get-played/</ref> a podcast about low-rated and weird video games.\n\nAs a television writer, Wiger's extensive career spans a wide range of work including the FOX sketch show ''[[Party Over Here]]'' (where he was head writer), Sarah Silverman's [[I Love You, America with Sarah Silverman|''I Love You, America'']], the long-running Comedy Central game show ''[[@midnight]]'', and the TV show version of [[Scott Aukerman]]'s [[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|''Comedy Bang! Bang!'']] <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4696339/</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWiger was raised in [[Long Beach]], [[California]] and is an alumnus of [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School]].\n\n==Career==\nWiger began his career as a video game tester and designer.<ref>https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,136235/</ref> After dropping out of college,{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} he began studying, performing, and teaching as an [[improv]] and sketch comedian at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theater]] (UCB) in [[Los Angeles]]. He most notably was a member of the sketch and improv team A Kiss From Daddy, alongside comedians [[Paul Rust]], [[Eva Anderson]], [[Michael Blaiklock|Mookie Blaiklock]], [[Neil Campbell (producer)|Neil Campbell]], [[Michael Cassady]], [[Dave Horwitz]], [[Allan McLeod]], and [[Harris Wittels]].<ref>https://franklin.ucbtheatre.com/show/1915</ref>\n\n===''Doughboys''===\nWiger created the comedy podcast ''[[Doughboys (podcast)|Doughboys]]'' with comedy writer [[Mike Mitchell (actor)|Mike Mitchell]] in 2015. ''[[Doughboys (podcast)|Doughboys]]'' was named \"The One Food Podcast to Start With\" by pop culture site Vulture.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite news|last=Legaspi|first=Althea|title=The One Podcast to Start With, Across 24 Topics|pages=|publisher=Vulture|date=2015-10-05|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/one-podcast-to-start-with-across-24-topics.html|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref> The co-hosts review chain restaurants with a weekly guest, including [[Nicole Byer]], [[Haley Joel Osment]], [[Sarah Silverman]], among others.<ref>https://headgum.com/doughboys</ref> Wiger's fans call him the \"Burger Boy\" and refer to themselves as members of the \"Burger Brigade\".\n\nAs of early 2018, the podcast is no longer associated with [[Feral Audio]] and is now a member of the [[HeadGum]] network. Mitchell and Wiger use [[Patreon]] to bring exclusive paid ''Doughboys'' content to their subscribers beyond the weekly episodes. As of February 2020, the ''Doughboys'' Patreon is the 9th most popular podcast Patreon and the 27th most popular Patreon in general.<ref>https://graphtreon.com/creator/doughboys</ref>\n\n===''How Did This Get Played?''===\nSince June 2019, Wiger is also the co-host (with [[Heather Anne Campbell]]) of [[How Did This Get Played? (podcast)|''How Did This Get Played?'']], a podcast about \"the worst and weirdest\" video games.<ref>https://www.earwolf.com/show/how-did-this-get-played/</ref> The name is derived from fellow [[Earwolf]] podcast ''[[How Did This Get Made?]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|4696339}}\n*{{Instagram|nickwiger}}\n*{{Twitter|nickwiger}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiger, Nick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Upright Citizens Brigade Theater performers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toImprov(link changed toImprovisational theatre) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nick_Wiger"}
{"title_page": "Maglaj", "text_new": "{{More references|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = Maglaj\n|settlement_type = [[List of cities in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Town]] and [[Municipalities of Bosnia and Herzegovina|municipality]]\n|image_skyline = Maglaj (collage).jpg\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n|subdivision_type1      = Entity\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina|The Federation]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Cantons of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Canton]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Zenica-Doboj Canton|Zenica-Doboj]]\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|map_caption =Location of Maglaj within Bosnia and Herzegovina.\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|leader_title=Municipality&nbsp;president|\nnative_name = \u041c\u0430\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0458|\nimage_shield = Emblem of Maglaj.svg|\nimage_coat_of_arms_size = 100px|\n|\n|\nleader_name = Mirsad Mahmutagi\u0107 ([[Party of Democratic Action|SDP]])\n|area_total_km2 = 290\n|population_total = 24980\n|population_as_of = 2013 census\n| population_density_km2 = 86\nimage_map = Maglaj Municipality Location.svg|\n|pushpin_map            =Bosnia and Herzegovina\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Maglaj\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|44|33|N|18|06|E|region:BA|display=inline}}\n|\narea_code = +387 32|\nparts = |\nwebsite = {{url|http://www.maglaj.net}}|\n}}\n'''Maglaj''' is a town and municipality located in [[Zenica-Doboj Canton]] of the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], an entity of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It is located in northern Bosnia and Herzegovina, {{convert|25|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Doboj]]. It has a population of 24,980 inhabitants.\n\n==Population==\n\n=== Population ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"7\" |Population of settlements \u2013 Maglaj municipality\n|-\n|\n|Settlement\n|1961.\n|1971.\n|1981.\n|1991.\n|2013.\n|-\n|\n|Total\n|32,944\n|38,037\n|42,160\n|43,388\n|23,146\n|-\n|1\n|Bijela Plo\u010da\n|\n|\n|\n|1,004\n|616\n|-\n|2\n|Bradi\u0107i Donji\n|\n|\n|\n|664\n|462\n|-\n|3\n|Bradi\u0107i Gornji\n|\n|\n|\n|567\n|430\n|-\n|4\n|\u010cobe\n|\n|\n|\n|654\n|635\n|-\n|5\n|Domislica\n|\n|\n|\n|703\n|679\n|-\n|6\n|Donja Bo\u010dinja\n|\n|\n|\n|821\n|214\n|-\n|7\n|Donji Uli\u0161njak\n|\n|\n|\n|634\n|585\n|-\n|8\n|Jablanica\n|\n|\n|\n|1,570\n|864\n|-\n|9\n|Kopice\n|\n|\n|\n|1,231\n|1,227\n|-\n|10\n|Kosova\n|\n|\n|\n|1,745\n|1,809\n|-\n|11\n|Lije\u0161nica\n|\n|\n|\n|1,807\n|1,576\n|-\n|12\n|'''Maglaj'''\n|\n|5,952\n|6,913\n|7,957\n|6,438\n|-\n|13\n|Misuri\u0107i\n|\n|\n|\n|1,937\n|1,556\n|-\n|14\n|Mlado\u0161evica\n|\n|\n|\n|866\n|720\n|-\n|15\n|Mo\u0161evac\n|\n|\n|\n|1,270\n|1,490\n|-\n|16\n|Novi \u0160eher\n|\n|\n|\n|1,802\n|1,495\n|-\n|17\n|Ravna\n|\n|\n|\n|516\n|476\n|-\n|18\n|Strupina\n|\n|\n|\n|749\n|536\n|-\n|19\n|Tujnica\n|\n|\n|\n|480\n|370\n|}\n\n=== Ethnic composition ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"8\" |Ethnic composition \u2013 Maglaj town\n|-\n|\n|2013.\n|1991.\n|1981.\n|1971.\n|-\n|Total\n|6,438 (100,0%)\n|7,957 (100,0%)\n|6,913 (100,0%)\n|5,952 (100,0%)\n|-\n|Bosniaks\n|\n|4,292 (53,94%)\n|3,422 (49,50%)\n|3,421 (57,48%)\n|-\n|Serbs\n|\n|1,975 (24,82%)\n|1,585 (22,93%)\n|1,593 (26,76%)\n|-\n|Yugoslavs\n|\n|1,026 (12,89%)\n|1,419 (20,53%)\n|197 (3,310%)\n|-\n|Croats\n|\n|446 (5,605%)\n|416 (6,018%)\n|582 (9,778%)\n|-\n|Others\n|\n|218 (2,740%)\n|30 (0,434%)\n|112 (1,882%)\n|-\n|Albanians\n|\n|\n|15 (0,217%)\n|10 (0,168%)\n|-\n|Montenegrins\n|\n|\n|14 (0,203%)\n|14 (0,235%)\n|-\n|Slovenes\n|\n|\n|11 (0,159%)\n|22 (0,370%)\n|-\n|Macedonians\n|\n|\n|1 (0,014%)\n|1 (0,017%)\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"9\" |Sastav stanovni\u0161tva \u2013 op\u0107ina Maglaj\n|-\n|\n|2013.\n|1991.\n|1981.\n|1971.\n|1961.\n|-\n|Total\n|23,146 (100,0%)\n|43,388 (100,0%)\n|42,160 (100,0%)\n|38,037 (100,0%)\n|32,944 (100,0%)\n|-\n|Bosniaks\n|19,810 (85,59%)\n|19,569 (45,10%)\n|17,236 (40,88%)\n|15,628 (41,09%)\n|7,998 (24.28%)\n|-\n|Croats\n|2,041 (8,818%)\n|8,365 (19,28%)\n|8,341 (19,78%)\n|7,946 (20,89%)\n|7,313 (22.20%)\n|-\n|Serbs\n|810 (3,500%)\n|13,312 (30,68%)\n|13,662 (32,41%)\n|13,888 (36,51%)\n|13,870  (42.10%)\n|-\n|Others\n|485 (2,095%)\n|634 (1,461%)\n|164 (0,389%)\n|257 (0,676%)\n|215 (0.65%)\n|-\n|Yugoslavs\n|\n|1,508 (3,476%)\n|2,682 (6,361%)\n|240 (0,631%)\n|3,548 (10.77%)\n|-\n|Montenegrins\n|\n|\n|40 (0,095%)\n|38 (0,100%)\n|\n|-\n|Albanians\n|\n|\n|18 (0,043%)\n|15 (0,039%)\n|\n|-\n|Slovenes\n|\n|\n|12 (0,028%)\n|22 (0,058%)\n|\n|-\n|Macedonians\n|\n|\n|5 (0,012%)\n|2 (0,005%)\n|\n|-\n|Roma\n|\n|\n|\n|1 (0,003%)\n|\n|}\n\n==Geography==\nThe town is situated in the northern part of Bosnia and Herzegovina and is situated in territory where [[Bosniaks]] presently form a large majority. The old Maglaj, like numerous other cities in Bosnia and Herzegovina, has an old town with mosques, traditional houses dating back from the [[Ottoman Empire]], and a fortress that stands as a symbol of Maglaj. The new part of Maglaj, situated on the West side of the river [[Bosna (river)|Bosna]], is made up of modern architecture that was started in the 1950s, and became massively developed until 1991.\n\nThe Bosna flows through Maglaj on its way north to the [[Sava]] river on the border between Bosnia and Herzegovina and [[Croatia]]. Before the [[Bosnian War]], the Bosna river was heavily polluted due to heavy industrial activity at the nearby [[Natron]] paper and pulp factory, as well as steel and wood industry factories in the southern cities of [[Zenica]] and [[Zavidovi\u0107i]] respectively. Nowadays, the river has become cleaner due to decreased industrial activity at those plants and higher environmental standards.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{unsourced|section|date=September 2018}}\nThe city, as well as the entire Maglaj municipality, have been subject to a large demographic population shift.  Close to all of its pre-war Christian inhabitants, i.e. [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Orthodox Serbs]] and [[Roman Catholicism in Croatia|Catholic Croats]], who made up the majority of the pre-war municipality population, no longer reside in the Maglaj municipality. \n\nThe Orthodox population has largely settled in the [[Doboj]] and [[Modri\u010da]] regions of the [[Republika Srpska]], while the Catholic population has settled in the nearby municipality of [[\u017dep\u010de]], an enclave inhabited largely by Croats. A significant number of former Croat inhabitants have also settled in Croatia's capital [[Zagreb]]. \n\nDue to the severe fighting around Maglaj throughout the Bosnian War, and the catastrophic conditions it was exposed to, numerous [[Bosniaks|Bosniak]] Muslims have departed the region as well.\n\nPre-war Maglaj was unique because over one third of its married couples were made up of mixed ethnic groups. As a result of this, a great number of these Maglaj inhabitants felt welcome by none of the three warring ethnic groups, and tried to settle abroad. Consequentially, Maglaj residents have dispersed.\n\n==History==\nMaglaj originated in the 14th century. The [[river Bosna]] goes through this town.\n\nFrom 1929 to 1941, Maglaj was part of the [[Vrbas Banovina]] of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]].\n\nThe city endured a long siege by [[Bosnian Serb]]s forces between 1993 and 1994 during the [[Bosnian War]], when the area was the scene of heavy fighting and the population had to be supplied by [[airdrop]]s.\n\nThe last flooding occurred on May 16, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = In Pictures: Severe flooding in Bosnia|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/inpictures/2014/05/pictures-severe-flooding-bosnia-20145201694397896.html|website = www.aljazeera.com|accessdate = 2015-06-03|first = Lejla|last = Osmic}}</ref> Although little floods occur every year, the 2014 flood was major, people lost their homes and belongings.\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Admir Hasan\u010di\u0107]], former football player\n*[[Alma \u010card\u017ei\u0107]], singer\n*[[Bahrudin \u010cengi\u0107]], film director and screenwriter\n*[[\u0160emsa Suljakovi\u0107]], singer\n*[[Edhem Mulabdi\u0107]], Writer\n*[[Ru\u017ea Toma\u0161i\u0107]], politician and [[European Parliament]] member\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Maglaj}}\n*http://www.maglaj.net/\n*[http://www.bhtourism.ba/eng/tbk.wbsp Tragovima bosanskog kraljevstva] - Tourist route for medieval Bosnia (English)\n*[http://www.bosnia.ba/ Trail of the Bosnian Kingdom] - Cultural Tourism in Tesanj\n\n{{Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{Zenica-Doboj Canton}}\n{{Maglaj municipality}}\n{{coord|44|33|N|18|06|E|region:BA_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Maglaj| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Maglaj]]\n", "text_old": "{{More references|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|official_name = Maglaj\n|settlement_type = [[List of cities in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Town]] and [[Municipalities of Bosnia and Herzegovina|municipality]]\n|image_skyline = Maglaj (collage).jpg\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n|subdivision_type1      = Entity\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina|The Federation]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Cantons of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Canton]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Zenica-Doboj Canton|Zenica-Doboj]]\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|map_caption =Location of Maglaj within Bosnia and Herzegovina.\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|leader_title=Municipality&nbsp;president|\nnative_name = \u041c\u0430\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0458|\nimage_shield = Emblem of Maglaj.svg|\nimage_coat_of_arms_size = 100px|\n|\n|\nleader_name = Mirsad Mahmutagi\u0107 ([[Party of Democratic Action|SDP]])\n|area_total_km2 = 290\n|population_total = 24980\n|population_as_of = 2013 census\n| population_density_km2 = 86\nimage_map = Maglaj Municipality Location.svg|\n|pushpin_map            =Bosnia and Herzegovina\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Maglaj\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|44|33|N|18|06|E|region:BA|display=inline}}\n|\narea_code = +387 32|\nparts = |\nwebsite = {{url|http://www.maglaj.net}}|\n}}\n'''Maglaj''' is a town and municipality located in [[Zenica-Doboj Canton]] of the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], an entity of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. It is located in northern Bosnia and Herzegovina, {{convert|25|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Doboj]]. It has a population of 24,980 inhabitants.\n\n==Population==\n\n===1961-2013===\n{|border=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"clear:all; margin:6px 0 0em 0em; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:65%; empty-cells:show\"\n|colspan=\"6\" align=center style=\"background:#778899; color:white\"|'''Ethnic Composition'''\n|-\n|- align=center\n|''[[Bosniaks]]''\n|''[[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serbs]]''\n|''[[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Croats]]''\n|''[[Yugoslavs]]''\n|''Others''\n|''Total''\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"#cccc99\" align=center |'''1961'''\n|- bgcolor=\"f5f5f5\" align=center\n| 7,998 24.28%|| 13,870 42.10%|| 7,313 22.20%|| 3,548 10.77%||   215  0.65%|| 32,944\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"#cccc99\" align=center |'''1971'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#f5f5f5\" align=center\n| 15,628 41.09%|| 13,888 36.51%||  7,946 20.89%||    240  0.63%||   335  0.88%|| 38,037\n|-\n|colspan=\"6