ss members who died in office]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thomas Gill (politician)|Thomas Gill]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Hawaii|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Hawaii's at-large congressional district]]|years=1965\u20131971}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Hawaii|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Hawaii's 2nd congressional district]]|years=1971\u20131977}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Daniel Akaka]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Daniel Akaka]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Hawaii|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Hawaii's 2nd congressional district]]|years=1990\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ed Case]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Norman Mineta]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]|years=1995\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert A. Underwood|Robert Underwood]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leonor Sullivan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Caucus Vice-Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|Secretary of the House Democratic Caucus]]|years=1975\u20131977}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Shirley Chisholm]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frederick Irving]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Secretary of State for Oceans and International Environmental and Scientific Affairs]]|years=1977\u20131978}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas R. Pickering|Tom Pickering]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Hawaii Representatives}}\n{{United States presidential election, 1972}}\n{{National Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 89th\u201394th & 101st\u2013107th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Hawaii]]}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/89}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/90}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/91}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/92}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/93}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/94}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/101}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/102}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/103}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/104}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/105}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/106}}\n{{USCongRep/HI/107}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mink, Patsy}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n[[Category:American women of Japanese descent in politics]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Deaths from varicella zoster infection]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Female members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Female United States presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Democrats]]\n[[Category:Hawaii politicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Hawaii state senators]]\n[[Category:Honolulu City Council members]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American diplomats]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American feminists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Hawaii Territorial Legislature]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States Congress of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:People from Maui]]\n[[Category:People from Paia, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Politicians elected posthumously]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1972 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii at Manoa alumni]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American lawyer, politician, and civil rights activist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Patsy Mink\n|image        = patsymink.jpg\n|alt          = Black and white photographic portrait of a woman in a suit adorned with a pearl necklace\n|state        = [[Hawaii]]\n|office       = Member of the<br />[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br /> from [[Hawaii]]\n|term_start   = September 22, 1990\n|term_end     = September 28, 2002\n|predecessor  = [[Daniel Akaka]]\n|successor    = [[Ed Case]]\n|constituency = [[Hawaii's 2nd congressional district|2nd district]]\n|term_start2  = January 3, 1965\n|term_end2    = January 3, 1977\n|predecessor2 = [[Thomas Gill (politician)|Thomas Gill]]\n|successor2   = [[Daniel Akaka]]\n|constituency2= [[Hawaii's at-large congressional district|At-large Seat B]] (1965\u201371)<br />[[Hawaii's 2nd congressional district|2nd district]] (1971\u201377)\n|office3      = Member of the [[Honolulu City Council]]<br />from the 9th district\n|term_start3  = December 1, 1982\n|term_end3    = December 1, 1986\n|predecessor3 =\n|successor3   = John DeSoto\n|office4      = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Oceans and International Environmental and Scientific Affairs]]\n|president4   = [[Jimmy Carter]]\n|term_start4  = March 28, 1977\n|term_end4    = May 1, 1978\n|predecessor4 = [[Frederick Irving]]\n|successor4   = [[Thomas R. Pickering]]\n|office5      = [[Democratic Caucus Vice-Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|Secretary of the House Democratic Caucus]]\n|leader5      = [[Carl Albert]]\n|term_start5  = January 3, 1975\n|term_end5    = January 3, 1977\n|predecessor5 = [[Leonor Sullivan]]\n|successor5   = [[Shirley Chisholm]]\n|birth_name   = Patsy Matsu Takemoto\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1927|12|6}}\n|birth_place  = H\u0101m\u0101kua Poko, [[Territory of Hawaii|Hawaii Territory]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = {{nowrap|{{death date and age|2002|9|28|1927|12|6}}}}\n|death_place  = [[Honolulu|Honolulu, Hawaii]], U.S.\n|restingplace = [[National Cemetery of the Pacific]]\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = John Mink\n|children     = 1\n|education    = [[Wilson College (Pennsylvania)|Wilson College]]<br />{{nowrap|[[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln]]}}<br />[[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[University of Chicago]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n\n'''Patsy Matsu Takemoto Mink''' (December 6, 1927 \u2013 September 28, 2002) was an American lawyer and politician from the [[U.S. state]] of [[Hawaii]]. Mink was a third generation [[Japanese American]], having been born and raised on the island of [[Maui]]. After graduating as [[valedictorian]] of the [[Maui High School]] class in 1944, she attended the [[University of Hawaii at M\u0101noa]] for two years and subsequently enrolled at the [[University of Nebraska]], where she experienced racism and worked to have [[Racial segregation|segregation]] [[Separate but equal|policies]] eliminated. After illness forced her to return to Hawaii to complete her studies there, she applied to 12 medical schools to continue her education, but was rejected by all of them. Following a suggestion by her employer, she opted to study law and was accepted at the [[University of Chicago Law School]] in 1948. While at university, she met and married [[World War II]] veteran and former [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] navigator John Francis Mink. When they graduated in 1951, Mink was unable to find employment as a married, Asian woman and after the birth of her daughter in 1952, the couple moved to Hawaii.\n\nWhen she was refused the right to take the bar examination, due to the loss of her Hawaiian residency upon marriage, Mink challenged the [[sexist]] statute. Though she won the right to take the test and passed the examination, no public or private firm would hire her because she was married and had a child. Mink's father helped her open her own practice in 1953 and around the same time she became a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. Hoping to work legislatively to change discriminatory customs through law, she worked as an attorney for the Hawaiian territorial legislature in 1955. The following year, she ran for a seat in the territorial [[Hawaii House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]. Winning the race, she became the first Japanese-American woman to serve in the territorial House and two years later, the first woman to serve in the territorial [[Hawaii Senate|Senate]], when she won her campaign for the higher house. In 1960, Mink gained national attention when she spoke in favor of the [[Civil rights movement|civil rights platform]] at the [[Democratic National Convention]] in Los Angeles.\n\nIn 1964, Mink ran for federal office and won a seat in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]. She was the first [[Person of color|woman of color]] and the first [[Asian American|Asian-American]] woman elected to Congress, and also the first woman elected to Congress from the state of [[Hawaii]]. She served a total of 12 terms, representing Hawaii's [[Hawaii's at-large congressional district|at-large]] and [[Second Congressional District of Hawaii|second]] congressional districts. While in Congress in the late 1960s, she introduced the first comprehensive initiatives under the [[Early Childhood Education Act]], which included the first federal child-care bill and worked on the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] of 1965. In 1970, she became the first person to oppose a [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] nominee on the basis of discrimination against women. Mink initiated a lawsuit which led to significant changes to presidential authority under the [[Freedom of Information Act]] in 1971. In 1972, she co-authored the [[Title IX|Title IX Amendment of the Higher Education Act]], later renamed the Patsy T. Mink Equal Opportunity in Education Act in 2002. \n\nMink was the first Asian-American woman to seek the presidential nomination of the Democratic Party. She ran in the [[1972 United States presidential election|1972 election]], standing in the [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 1972|Oregon primary]] as an anti-war candidate. She was [[Bureau of Oceans and International Environmental and Scientific Affairs|Assistant Secretary of State for Oceans and International Environmental and Scientific Affairs]] from 1977 to 1979. From 1980 to 1982, Mink served as the president of [[Americans for Democratic Action]] and then returned to Honolulu, where she was elected to the [[Honolulu City Council]], which she chaired until 1985. In 1990, she was again elected to the U.S. House, serving until her death in 2002. During her second six terms of office, she continued to work on legislation of importance to women, children, immigrants and minorities.\n\n== Family background ==\nPatsy Matsu Takemoto was born on December 6, 1927 at the sugar plantation camp, [[Hamakuapoko, Hawaii|H\u0101m\u0101kua Poko]], near [[Paia, Hawaii|Paia]], on the island of [[Maui]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=572}}{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}} Her parents were second-generation Japanese Americans{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=573}} or ''[[Nisei]]''. She was a ''[[Sansei]]'', or third-generation descendant of Japanese emigrants.{{sfn|Nomura|1998|pp=288, 290}} Her mother, Mitama Tateyama, was a [[homemaker]],{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}}{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}} and the daughter of Gojiro Tateyama and Tsuru Wakashige.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=574}}{{sfn|FamilySearch|1905}} Their family, which had 11 children, lived in a [[shack]] by the Waikamoi Stream. William Pogue, Gojiro's employer, arranged to have Tateyama's daughters educated at the Maunaolu Seminary, a [[boarding school]] for [[Christians|Christian]] girls located in the town of [[Makawao, Hawaii|Makawao]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=574}}\n\nTakemoto's maternal grandparents were both born in the [[Empire of Japan]] during the 19th century.{{sfn|FamilySearch|1933}} Gojiro Tateyama arrived in the [[Territory of Hawaii]] late in the century, and was employed on a [[sugarcane]] [[Sugar plantations in Hawaii|plantation]]. He later moved to Maui, where he was initially employed as a worker for the [[East Maui Irrigation Company]]. Subsequently, he was employed as a [[store manager]] and [[filling station]] employee. He also delivered mail throughout the [[backcountry]] of Maui.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=574}}\n\nHer father, Suematsu Takemoto, was a [[civil engineer]].{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}}{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}} He graduated from the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] in 1922, the first Japanese American to graduate from the University of Hawaii with a degree in civil engineering. For several years, he was the only Japanese-American civil engineer working at the sugar plantation in Maui.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=573}} Suematsu was passed over for promotion to chief engineer several times during his career, the positions instead being offered to mostly [[white American]]s. He resigned his local position in 1945 in the aftermath of [[World War II]], and moved to [[Honolulu, Hawaii|Honolulu]] with his family, where he established his own [[Surveying|land surveying company]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=574}}\n\n== Early years and education ==\nTakemoto began her education at the H\u0101m\u0101kua Poko Grammar School when she was four and then transferred in 4th grade to the Kaunoa English Standard School{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}} a mostly-white school attended only by students who could speak English and pass the entrance examination. She felt isolated and found the atmosphere unfriendly.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=576}} She entered [[Maui High School]] one year before Honolulu was [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked by Japan]]. Despite the local Japanese being treated as if they were enemies, Takemoto ran for and won her first election, becoming student body president in her senior year.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=577}} She was the first girl to serve as president of the student body{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=46}}{{sfn|Lee|2018}} and graduated as class [[valedictorian]] in 1944.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=578}}\n\n[[File:University of Hawaii Oratorical Contest Winners 1948.png|thumb |alt=Photograph of a group of four young women standing between two young men.|University of Hawaii Oratorical Contest Winners 1948 \u2013 L-R: front, Esther Belarmino, 3rd place; Patsy Takemoto, 1st place; Eichi Oki, finalist; back, Barry Rubin, finalist; Alice Mayo, finalist; and Jean McKillop, 2nd place]]\nTakemoto moved to Honolulu where she attended the University of Hawaii at M\u0101noa with medical school and a career in medicine her ultimate goal. During her sophomore year, she was elected president of the Pre-Medical Students Club and was selected as a member of the varsity debate team. In 1946, she decided to move to the mainland and spent one semester enrolled at [[Wilson College (Pennsylvania)|Wilson College]], a small women's college in [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=578}} Unsatisfied with the school, Takemoto transferred to the [[University of Nebraska]]. The university had a long-standing [[racial segregation]] policy whereby students of color lived in different dormitories from the [[white people|white]] students. This angered Takemoto, and she organized and created a coalition of students, parents, administrators, employees, alumni, sponsoring businesses and corporations. She was elected president of the Unaffiliated Students of the University of Nebraska, a \"separate\" student government for non-white students who were prevented from joining fraternities, sororities, and regular dormitories. Takemoto and her coalition successfully lobbied to end the university's segregation policies the same year.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=579}}\n\nAlthough her campaign was successful, in 1947 Takemoto experienced a serious thyroid condition that required surgery and moved back to Honolulu to recover and finish her final year of college at the University of Hawaii.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=580}} In 1948, she earned [[bachelor's degree]]s in [[zoology]] and [[chemistry]] from the university.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}} She began applying to medical schools, but none of the dozen schools to which she applied would accept her because she was a woman, especially as they were receiving large numbers of applications from returning veterans. She briefly worked as a typist at [[Hickam Air Force Base]] and then went to work at the [[Honolulu Academy of Arts]]. Her supervisor there, Jessie Purdy Restarick, encouraged her to consider a career in law.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=580}}\n\nTakemoto applied to both [[Columbia University]] and the [[University of Chicago Law School]] in the summer of 1948. Columbia rejected her outright, as the term was starting within months.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=580}} The University of Chicago admitted her as a foreign student{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=581}} and there was only one other woman in her class. Although she had a difficult time adjusting to the harsh winters,{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=46}} and she found her courses tedious, Takemoto became a popular figure at the International House.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=581}} While playing [[Contract bridge|bridge]] there one evening, she met John Francis Mink, a former [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] navigator and [[World War II]] veteran,{{sfn|Borreca|2005|p=C5}} who was enrolled in geology classes.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}} Against her parents' wishes, she and Mink married in January 1951, six months after meeting.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=582}} That spring, she obtained her [[Juris Doctor]] degree{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}}{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}} and John graduated as well, with a master's degree in geology.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}}\n\n== Family and early career ==\n===Law===\nUnable to find work as a married, female, Asian-American attorney, Mink returned to her student job at the University of Chicago Law School library while her husband found work immediately with the [[U.S. Steel|United States Steel Corporation]]. In 1952, she gave birth to daughter Gwendolyn (Wendy),{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=582}} who later became an educator and prominent author on law, poverty, and women's issues.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=46}} In August the family decided to move to Hawaii where John found work with the [[Hawaiian Sugar Planters' Association]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=582}} To practice law, Mink needed to pass her bar examination, but when she applied her residency was questioned.{{#tag:ref|The [[Cable Act]] of 1922 had repealed the federal statue which required a woman to give up her citizenship in favor of her husband's,{{sfn|Hacker|2014|pp=57-58}} if her husband was a citizen or eligible to be naturalized.{{sfn|Hacker|2014|p=59}} Amendments to the Cable Act continued until 1940 before married women were granted their own status as citizens without restriction.{{sfn|Hacker|2014|pp=60-61}} However, until the 1960s, legislative variations among the states, led to extremely different civil rights for women within the federal system depending upon their residency.{{sfn|Carlson|2007|p=262}}|group=\"Notes\"}}{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|pp=582\u2013583}}  The territorial law, in force at the time regarding married women, had removed her Hawaiian residency, making her a resident of her husband's state.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}} Proving that she had never resided in her husband's home state of Pennsylvania, she challenged the territorial law as [[sexist]].{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=246}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|pp=582\u2013583}} [[Attorney General of Hawaii|Hawaii's attorney general]] ruled in her favor and allowed her to take the examination as a Hawaiian resident.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}} Passing the test, Mink became \"the first Japanese-American woman licensed to practice law in Hawaii\".{{sfn|Gootman|2002}}\n\n[[File:Young Democratic Club of Hawaii 1954.png|thumb|alt=Photograph of a young woman looking at a paper, surrounded by four men.|Young Democratic Club of Hawaii 1954: \u2013 L-R: seated Representative O. Vincent Esposito, Patsy Mink (chair), and Senator William H. Heen; standing, Duke Cahill (secretary) and W. C. Wong (vice-chair)]]\nDespite passing the bar exam in June 1953, Mink continued to face discrimination as she sought employment as an attorney. No firms in the private or public sector, even those headed by Japanese Americans, were willing to hire a married woman with a child.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}} With the help of her father, she established a private firm and began teaching law courses at the University of Hawaii to earn money while she built her practice.{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}} With the opening of her firm, Mink became the first Asian-American woman to practice law in the Hawaiian territory.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=46}} Her firm took cases in [[Criminal law|criminal]] and [[family law]], which other firms typically avoided.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}} She began to be active in politics{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}} and founded the Everyman Organization, a group that served as the hub of the Young Democrats club on Oahu. She was elected \"chairman of the territory-wide Young Democrats\", which according to Esther K. Arinaga and Renee E. Ojiri was \"a group that would wield a remarkable influence over Hawaiian politics for several decades\".{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}}\n\n===State and territorial politics===\nIn 1954, Mink worked to help elect [[John A. Burns]] to Congress, though he lost the race.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}} The following year, she worked as staff attorney during the 1955 legislative session and drafted statutes, while observing the inner-workings of the legislature.{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=583}} As the Territory of Hawaii debated statehood in 1956, Mink was elected to the Hawaiian Territorial Legislature representing the Fifth District in the territorial [[Hawaii House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]. Surprising the Democratic party leadership with her win,{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=585}} she became the first woman with Japanese ancestry to serve in the territorial House. Two years later, she was the first woman to serve in the territorial [[Hawaii Senate|Senate]].{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=183}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=586}} In 1959, Hawaii became the 50th state of the Union and Mink ran in the Democratic primary for the state's at-large [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. congressional]] seat. She was defeated by Territorial Senator [[Daniel Inouye]].{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=247}}{{sfn|''The Honolulu Star-Bulletin''|1959a|p=23}}{{sfn|''The Honolulu Star-Bulletin''|1959b|p=3}} From 1962 to 1964, Mink served in the [[Hawaii State Senate]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=587}}{{sfn|United States Congress M000797|2020}}\n\n[[File:Official Portrait of the Hawaii Territorial Senate, 1958.png|thumb|alt=Photograph of 24 men both standing and seated surrounding a lone seated woman, in front of an American flag hanging between two Hawaiian flags|Mink, the sole woman in the 1958 Hawaii Territorial Senate]]\nDuring her time in the territorial legislature, Mink was known for her liberal positions and independent decision-making.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=586}}{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=184}} On her first day in office as a congresswoman in 1955, she submitted a resolution to ban the British from nuclear testing in the Pacific.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=247}} Dealing with a broad spectrum of socio-economic issues, she worked on legislation covering education, employment, housing, poverty, and taxation. She authored a bill in 1957 to grant \"equal pay for equal work\", regardless of gender, and was a staunch supporter of improving education, supporting legislation to increase per capita spending to better provide for children.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=586}}{{sfn|''The Honolulu Advertiser''|1957|p=2}} In 1960, Mink became vice-president of the National Young Democratic Clubs of America and worked on the [[Democratic National Convention]]'s Platform Committee drafting team.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=247}} That year at the [[1960 Democratic National Convention|national convention]] in [[Los Angeles]], she gained recognition when she spoke on the party's position in regard to civil rights. She urged that equal opportunity and equal protection be afforded to all Americans.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}} Motions to restrict the [[Civil rights movement|civil rights platform]] made by North Carolina Senator [[Sam Ervin]] were defeated and a platform to ensure equal rights and equal protection under the law to all citizens passed with the approval of two-thirds of the party.{{sfn|Roberts|1960|p=44-45}}{{sfn|Library of Congress|2008|p=20}}\n\n== Federal politics ==\n[[File:Washington, D.C. Women members of United States Congress, Seated, Senator Maurine Newberger, Oregon, Representative... - NARA - 541939.tif|thumb|alt=A group photograph of 12 women, three sitting and 9 standing, wearing in business dresses|Washington, D.C. Women members of United States Congress, Seated, Senator Maurine Newberger, Oregon, Representative... - NARA - 541939|1965 Congresswomen \u2014 L-R: Seated, Senator [[Maurine Neuberger]], Oregon; Representative [[Frances Bolton]], Ohio; Senator [[Margaret Chase Smith]], Maine; Standing, Representatives, [[Florence Dwyer]], New Jersey; [[Martha Griffiths]], Michigan; [[Edith Green]], Oregon; Patsy Mink, Hawaii; [[Leonor Sullivan]], Missouri; [[Julia Hansen]], Washington; [[Edna Kelly]], New York; and [[Charlotte Reid]], Illinois.]]\n\n===U.S. Representative (1965\u20131977)===\nDeciding to vie for a federal seat, Mink campaigned and won a post in the [[1964 United States House of Representatives elections|U.S. House]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=587}} As a result, she became the first Hawaiian woman elected to Congress,{{sfn|Zhao|2009|p=75}} the first [[Person of color|woman of color]] elected to the House,{{sfn|Democratic National Committee|2007}} the \"youngest member from the youngest state, as well as the first Japanese-American woman member in Congress\".{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=184}} Serving six consecutive terms, she was in office from 1965 to 1977.{{sfn|United States Congress M000797|2020}}{{sfn|Leavitt|1985|p=184}} Her independent nature continued to guide her decisions{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=49}} and she focused on issues that had been important to her in the Hawaiian legislature, such as children, education, and gender equality.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}} Mink supported the [[Great Society]] programs of President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], though she was openly critical of the [[Vietnam War]].{{sfn|Glass|2017}} \n\nSeeking and attaining a post on the Committee on Education and Labor, on which she would serve throughout her first tenure (1965\u20131977), Mink introduced in the late 1960s the first comprehensive initiatives under the [[Early Childhood Education Act]], which included the first federal child-care bill and bills establishing bilingual education, [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]], school lunch programs, [[special education]], student loans, and teacher sabbaticals.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}}{{sfn|Office of the Historian|Clerk of the House|2003}}{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=7}}  She also worked on the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] of 1965 and bills promoting adult education, Asian studies, career guidance programs, and vocational education. Her day-care bill proposed in 1967, was the first bill of its kind to pass both houses of Congress. Passed in 1971, the bill was vetoed by President [[Richard Nixon]].{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=7}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=588}} In her second term, during the [[90th United States Congress|90th Congress]], Mink was appointed to the [[Committee on Interior and Insular Affairs]].{{sfn|Office of the Historian|Clerk of the House|2003}}\n\n[[File:Patsy Mink Lyndon Johnson.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A photograph of a man and a woman wearing leis waving to the photographer standing on the landing of a Pan Am Airlines boarding ramp|Mink with Lyndon Johnson after his trip to Hawaii for a conference on the Vietnam War, February 1966.]]\nIn 1970, Mink became the first Democratic woman to deliver a [[State of the Union#Opposition response|State of the Union]] response and only the second woman to respond to the address.{{sfn|Woodruff|2015}} That year, she was the first witness to testify against President Nixon's [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] nominee [[G. Harrold Carswell|George Harrold Carswell]]. In her testimony, she cited his refusal to hear the case brought to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|5th Circuit Court of Appeals]] regarding Ida Phillips' employment discrimination case. Phillips had been denied a position because she was a woman with children and Mink's objection highlighted for the first time in an evaluation of a court nominee, the inequalities faced by working women. Carswell would eventually be rejected by the Senate. [[Harry Blackmun]], who wrote the majority opinion in [[Roe v. Wade]], would later be confirmed instead.{{sfn|Lee|2018}}\n\nMink sued the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] in 1971, to obtain copies of documents that were being withheld by Nixon's office with regard to nuclear testing on [[Amchitka Island]]. Believing that under the [[Freedom of Information Act]] agency reports connected to the test should be released, she led 32 congress members in the attempt to secure the reports. The District Court ruled that the documents \"were exempt from compelled disclosure\" and the test was performed in November 1971. The [[United States courts of appeals|Court of Appeals]] reversed the decision of the lower court ruling that an ''[[in camera]]'' inspection of sensitive documents might determine that some could be released. Escalated to the Supreme Court, the decision issued reversed the appeals deicision and confirmed that court inspection could not override the executive's exemption. The Court did allow that Congress could change the law with regard to the regulation of executive actions. In 1974, Congress authorized private scrutiny of documents withheld by the executive. President [[Gerald Ford]] vetoed the legislation, but his veto was overridden by Congress.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|pp=588\u2013589}}\n\nFrustrated by the roll-backs by the Nixon administration of civil liberties and the continuance of the Vietnam War, Mink entered the presidential race in 1971 hoping to become the Democratic Party's nominee.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=590}} She was the first Asian-American woman to run for president.{{sfn|Ettinger|McDowell|2020}} As Hawaii had no primary, her name appeared on the Oregon ballot for 1972,{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=590}} as an anti-war candidate.{{sfn|Kua|2002}} During her campaign, she flew to Paris with [[Bella Abzug]], U.S. Representative of New York, to press for the resumption of [[Paris Peace Accords|peace talks]]. Arriving in April, the women met with [[Nguy\u1ec5n Th\u1ecb B\u00ecnh]], foreign minister for [[North Vietnam]], as well as representatives for the [[South Vietnam|South Vietnamese]] and United States governments.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=590}} Her actions drew strong criticism, fostering a campaign by Democrats in her home state to oppose her next term in Congress.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}} In May, she lost the presidential primary, failing to secure enough delegates to support her candidacy, earning only 2% of the 50 potential delegates.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=590}}{{sfn|Walsh|1972|p=1}} [[File:Patsy Mink 1970s.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Photographic portrait of a smiling Asian woman in a sleeveless blouse|1972 campaign poster image from the Patsy Mink for President Committee]]\n\nMink co-authored and advocated for the passage of [[Title IX Amendment of the Higher Education Act]], prohibiting gender discrimination by federally funded institutions of higher education. President Nixon signed the Act into law in 1972.{{sfn|Lee|2018}} She also introduced the [[Women's Educational Equity Act]] of 1974,{{sfn|Glass|2017}}{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=7}} which allocated funds for the promotion of gender equity in schools. The law opened employment and education opportunities for women and opposed gender stereotypes in curricula and textbooks.{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=48}} In addition to her work on education issues, Mink promoted numerous laws that dealt with other issues important to women. These included the [[Consumer Product Safety Act|Consumer Product Safety]] and Equal Employment Opportunity Acts of 1972; the [[Equal Credit Opportunity Act]] of 1974;{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=7}} and various bills dealing with discrimination in insurance practices, pensions, retirement benefits, social security, survivor's benefits and taxation; equitable jury service; health care issues; housing discrimination based on marital status; and privacy issues. In 1973, she authored and introduced the Equal Rights for Women Act (H.R. 4034), which never made it out of committee, and she supported the ratification of the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=7}}{{sfn|U.S. Congress|2002}} \n\nIn 1975, Mink attended the [[World Conference on Women, 1975|World Conference on Women]] held in [[Mexico City]] from mid-June to early July.{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=7}} Together with Abzug and Representative [[Margaret Heckler]] of Massachusetts, she pledged to sponsor and support legislation for a U.S. women's conference for the [[United States Bicentennial]].{{sfn|''The Charlotte News''|1975|p=5A}} When they returned home, Abzug introduced HR 9924, co-sponsored by Mink and others, which granted $5 million in total tax-payer contributions (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|5000000|1975|r=1}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) for both state and [[National Women's Conference]]s. It was signed into law by President Ford.{{sfn|U.S. Congress|1975}}{{sfn|Threinen|2001}} Later that year, an effort was made to exempt school athletics from the provisions of Title IX via the Casey Amendment. The Amendment proposed allowing schools to determine whether they would provide equal funding for men's and women's sporting activities. The exemption was struck from the Senate version of the appropriations bill. In the House, though Mink had lobbied heavily against the amendment to the appropriations bill (H.R. 5901), immediately before the vote was called she left the chamber, having received an emergency message that her daughter had been in a serious car accident in New York. In a 211 against and 212 for vote, the appropriation bill passed with the Casey Amendment intact. Upon her return from New York, Speaker [[Carl Albert]] of Oklahoma and other members of the House called for a revote due to the circumstances. July 17 members revoted and with 215 in favor to 178 against, the Casey Amendment was rejected; so protecting the anti-discrimination provisions of Title IX.{{sfn|Office of the Historian|Clerk of the House|2003}}{{sfn|''The Lansing State Journal''|1975|p=C3}}\n\nThroughout her tenure, Mink was involved in many congressional activities, including serving as vice-chair of the Democratic Study Group from 1966 through 1971. In 1968, she served as chair of the House-Senate Ad Hoc Committee on Poverty. From 1972 to 1976, she served on the House Budget Committee, chaired the Insular Affairs Subcommittee on mines and mining from 1973 to 1977 and from 1975 to 1976 was part of the Select Committee on the Outer Continental Shelf.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}} In 1976, learning that she had been given the experimental drug [[diethylstilbestrol]], during her pregnancy, which unwittingly placed both her and her daughter at risk of developing cancer, Mink brought a [[Class action|class action lawsuit]] against [[Eli Lilly and Company]] and the [[University of Chicago]]. The settlement entitled all 1,000 women affected, and their children, to free lifetime diagnostic testing and treatment at the [[University of Chicago Medical Center|Chicago Lying-In Clinic]].{{sfn|Mertens|2012|p=49}}{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=592}} That year, she also filed a complaint with the [[Federal Communications Commission]] which successfully required radio stations to provide equal air time to opposing views.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=249}} Mink introduced the [[Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act of 1977|Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act]], which was enacted in 1977.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}} From 1975 to 1977, during the [[94th Congress]], she was elected to a position in the House Democratic leadership, as [[Democratic Caucus Vice Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|Secretary of the House Democratic Caucus]].{{sfn|Office of the Clerk|2011}}\n\n===U.S. Assistant Secretary of State (1977\u20131979)===\nIn 1976, Mink gave up her seat in Congress to run for a vacancy in the United States Senate created by the retirement of Senator [[Hiram Fong]]. After she lost the [[primary election]] for the Senate seat to Hawaii's other U.S. Representative, [[Spark Matsunaga]], President [[Jimmy Carter]] appointed Mink as [[Assistant Secretary of State for Oceans and International Environmental and Scientific Affairs]].{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=592}} She worked on environmental issues such as deep-sea mining, toxic waste, and whale protection, holding the post from 1977 to 1979.{{sfn|United States Congress M000797|2020}}{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}}\n\n==Return to the private sector (1980\u20131987)==\nMink resigned from the Carter Administration in 1980, accepting a position as president of the [[Americans for Democratic Action]] in Washington, D. C. She was the first woman to head the national organization and served three consecutive one-year terms.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=593}} Returning to Honolulu, she was elected to the [[Honolulu City Council]] in 1983, serving as Chair until 1985.{{sfn|United States Congress M000797|2020}} She was regularly on opposite sides to the Republican Mayor of Honolulu [[Frank Fasi]], who was elected in 1984,{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=593}} though she remained on the council until 1987.{{sfn|United States Congress M000797|2020}} In 1986 she ran for governor of Hawaii and in 1988 for mayor of Honolulu, but was not successful in either bid for office.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=248}} When she left the city council, Mink began working for The Public Reporter, a watchdog committee that monitored and published reports on voting records and pending legislation. She also led the Hawaii Coalition on Global Affairs, a group which sponsored public lectures and workshops on international issues.{{sfn|Viotti|1989|p=B1}}\n\n== Later career (1990\u20132002) ==\n[[File:Formation of the Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of a woman standing at a podium, behind whom are a group of four men and one woman standing against a draped wall with a bookcase|Mink announcing the formation of the Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]\nIn 1990, Mink was elected to complete the remaining term of her successor in the House, [[Daniel Akaka]]. Akaka had been appointed to the Senate to succeed Matsunaga, who had recently died in office. She was elected to a full term six weeks later later, and subsequently was reelected six times.{{sfn|Arinaga|Ojiri|2003|p=594}} That year, she opposed the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|Supreme Court nominee]] [[Clarence Thomas]]. When the Senate Judiciary Committee denied [[Anita Hill]] the opportunity to give testimony, Mink, and other congresswomen, including [[Barbara Boxer]] of California, [[Louise Slaughter]] of New York, and [[Pat Schroeder]] of Colorado, marched to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]] to protest the decision. Their protest was carried on the front page of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and Hill was later allowed to testify.{{sfn|Lee|2018}} \n\nIn her second tenure as a House member, Mink worked to revive protections in the socio-economic programs she had worked for in her first six terms, which had been scaled back by subsequent administrations.{{sfn|Glass|2017}} From 1990 to 1993, she worked on legislation sponsoring the Ovarian Cancer Research Act and amendments to the Higher Education Act. In 1992, she was honored by the [[American Bar Association]] with the Margaret Brent Women Lawyers Achievement Award for professional excellence.{{sfn|Fugita|1999|p=249}} She co-sponsored the Gender Equity Act of 1993, pressed for universal health care,{{sfn|Glass|2017}} and introduced a bill to protect reproductive decisions as an individual right.{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=11}}{{sfn|U.S. Congress|2002}} She worked on legislation regarding displaced homemakers, minimum wage increases, occupational safety, pay inequality, and violence against women.{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=11}}\n\n[[File:Congresswoman Patsy Mink 207-DP-8386B-DSC 0064 (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of an Asian woman in an orange blouse and white blazer|Mink, 2002]]\nIn May 1994, Mink and Representative [[Norman Mineta]] of California co-founded the [[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]] for which she became chair in 1995, serving until 1997. She also served as co-chair of the House Democratic Women's Caucus. Mink opposed legislation proposed by the Republican-majority House of the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]] on [[Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Act|welfare reform]] in 1996.{{sfn|Office of the Historian|Clerk of the House|2003}} She authored the Family Stability and Work Act as an alternative welfare reform measure and repeatedly, though mostly unsuccessfully, lobbied for increased federal safety nets for children and families living in impoverished conditions. She opposed legislation that would limit [[Product liability|liability for product injuries]] and work place discrimination and objected to the ratification of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]].{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=11}} She was a co-sponsor of the [[DREAM Act]]{{sfn|U.S. Congress|2002}} and staunchly opposed the creation of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]], fearing that it might avert civil liberties and result in another occurrence of policies like the [[Internment of Japanese Americans|internment camps for Japanese Americans]] during World War II.{{sfn|Gootman|2002}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn August 30, 2002, Mink was hospitalized in Honolulu's [[Straub Medical Center|Straub Clinic and Hospital]] due to complications from [[chickenpox]]. Her condition steadily worsened, and on September 28, 2002, she died in Honolulu of viral [[pneumonia]], at age 74.{{sfn|Gootman|2002}} In recognition of the national mourning of her death, Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]] ordered all flags at military institutions lowered to [[half-mast|half staff]] in her honor.{{sfn|Kua|2002}} Mink received a national memorial and was honored with a [[State funerals in the United States|state funeral]] held on October 4 in the [[Hawaii State Capitol|Hawaii State Capitol Rotunda]] attended by leaders and members of Congress.{{sfn|DePledge|2002|p=7}}{{sfn|Gordon|Nakase|2002|pp=1, 5}}  Women's groups honored Mink by forming a human lei of around 900 women who surrounded the tent where Mink's casket stood in the capital atrium and sang Hawaiian songs.{{sfn|Hoover|2002|p=A14}} She was buried at the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]], near the [[Punchbowl Crater]].{{sfn|DePledge|2002|p=7}}{{sfn|Gordon|Nakase|2002|pp=1, 5}}  \n\nMink's death occurred one week after she had won the 2002 primary election, too late for her name to be removed from the general election ballot.{{sfn|DePledge|2002|p=7}}{{sfn|''The Los Angeles Times''|2002}} On November 5, 2002, Mink was posthumously re-elected to Congress.{{sfn|''The New York Times''|2002}} Her vacant seat was filled by [[Ed Case]] after a special election on January 4, 2003.{{sfn|''CNN''|2003}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nMink is remembered as a woman who dealt with the personal discrimination she had felt as a woman and an Asian American by dedicating her career to creating public policies to open doors for women and minorities.{{sfn|Gordon|Nakase|2002|p=1}}{{sfn|Dobbin|2003|p=6}} In 2002 Congress renamed the Title IX Amendment of the Higher Education Act, which Mink had co-authored, as the \"[[Patsy T. Mink Equal Opportunity in Education Act]]\".{{sfn|Lee|2018}} Her papers were donated in 2002 and are housed in the [[Library of Congress]].{{sfn|McAleer|Femia|Brooks|2007|p=2}} In 2003 a scholarship program, the ''Patsy Takemoto Mink Education Foundation'', was established to provide educational funding for low-income women and children.{{sfn|''The Honolulu Advertiser''|2003b|p=B3}} That year, Mink was inducted into the [[National Women's Hall of Fame]],{{sfn|Dobbin|2003|p=6}} the Scholar-Athlete Hall of Fame of the Institute for International Sport,{{sfn|''The Honolulu Advertiser''|2003a|p=D4}} and the post office which served the area of Maui in which she grew up was renamed in her honor, after authorization by President [[George W. Bush]].{{sfn|Young|2003|p=3}} In 2007, [[Central Oahu Regional Park]] on [[Oahu]] was renamed \"Patsy T. Mink Central Oahu Regional Park\" in her honor.{{sfn|''Hawaii News Now''|2007}} She was honored posthumously with the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from President [[Barack Obama]] on November 24, 2014.{{sfn|Office of the Press Secretary|2014}}{{sfn|''NBC News''|2014}} \n\nDocumentary films about Mink's life and role in Title IX include the ''[[Patsy Mink: Ahead of the Majority]]'' (2008), directed by Kimberlee Bassford and ''Rise of the Wahine'' (2014), directed by Dean Kaneshiro.{{sfn|''The Honolulu Star-Bulletin''|2008|p=HIFF10}}{{sfn|Gordon|2014|p=F1}} The 2008 film highlighted the challenges Mink overcame and how that fueled her work on legislation to help others.{{sfn|''The Honolulu Star-Bulletin''|2008|p=HIFF10}} The 2014 film told the story of the University of Hawaii's [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|women's volleyball team]]'s struggle to build a team even after Title IX passed. As the bill was an educational funding law, women's athletic director, [[Donnis Thompson]] used it as leverage to expand sporting opportunities at the university in spite of intense opposition. Working together to ensure that lawmakers understood who they were representing, Mink had Thompson bring the team to Washington.{{sfn|Gordon|2014|pp=F1, F10}}{{sfn|Miller|2014|pp=C1, C3}}\n\n== Selected works ==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Mink |first1=Patsy |title=Education\u2014The Vision of America |journal=The School Counselor |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=5\u201312 |publisher=American School Counselor Association |issn=0036-6536 |date=September 1966 |oclc=5792465172}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Mink |first1=Patsy |title=The Status of Women |journal=Educational Horizons |volume=49 |issue=2 |pages=54\u201356 |publisher=Pi Lambda Theta |issn=0013-175X |date=December 1970 |oclc=5792526438}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Mink |first1=Patsy |title=Micronesia: Our Bungled Trust |journal=Texas International Law Forum |issue=6 |pages=181\u2013207 |publisher=University of Texas at Austin |issn=0040-4381 |date=1971 |oclc=16332426}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Mink |first1=Patsy |title=Energy and Environment: Which Is Undermining Which? |journal=Natural Resources Lawyer |issue=9 |pages=19\u201339 |publisher=American Bar Association |issn=2328-3416 |date=1976 |oclc=772508196}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Mink |first1=Patsy |title=Reclamation and Rollcalls: The Political Struggle over Stripmining |journal=Environmental Policy and Law |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=176\u2013180 |publisher=Elsevier Science Publishers |issn=0378-777X |date=1976 |oclc=4933180255}}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Mink | first1 = Patsy | last2 = Hartmann | first2 = Heidi I. | author-link2 = Heidi Hartmann | title = Wrap-up | journal = [[Social Justice (journal)|Social Justice]] | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 110\u2013113 | publisher = Social Justice/Global Options via [[JSTOR]] | date = Spring 1994 | jstor = 29766793}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Mink |first1=Patsy |title=Nuclear Waste: The Most Compelling Environmental Issue Facing the World Today |journal=Fordham Environmental Law Journal |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=165\u2013170 |publisher=Fordham University School of Law |issn=1079-6657 |date=October 1996 |oclc=7851122029}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Arinaga |first1=Esther K. |last2=Ojiri |first2=Renee E. |editor-last1=Cruz |editor-first1=Tania |editor-last2=Yamamoto |editor-first2=Eric K. |title=A Tribute to Patsy Takemoto Mink |journal=[[Asian-Pacific Law & Policy Journal]] |date=Summer 2003 |volume=4 |issue=2 |url=http://blog.hawaii.edu/aplpj/files/2011/11/APLPJ_04.2_cruz.pdf |accessdate=December 25, 2016 |publisher=[[William S. Richardson School of Law]] |issn=1541-244X |pages=569\u2013597 |postscript=. Reprinted original text from Mari Matsuda ed. ''Called from Within: Early Women Lawyers of Hawai'i'' (Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press, 1992). pp. 251\u2013280.}}\n*{{cite news |ref=harv |last1=Borreca |first1=Richard |title=Politician's 'Rock' Supported Her Throughout Her Career |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47176562/john-f-mink-2005-death/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |newspaper=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] |date=October 19, 2005 |location=Honolulu, Hawaii |pages=C5 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}