y}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n[[Category:American women of Japanese descent in politics]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Deaths from varicella zoster infection]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Female members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Female United States presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Democrats]]\n[[Category:Hawaii politicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Hawaii state senators]]\n[[Category:Honolulu City Council members]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American diplomats]]\n[[Category:Japanese-American feminists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Hawaii Territorial Legislature]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States Congress of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:People from Maui]]\n[[Category:People from Paia, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Politicians elected posthumously]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1972 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii at Manoa alumni]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patsy_Mink"}
{"title_page": "Will Bonsall", "text_new": "'''Will Bonsall''' is an American author, seed saver and veganic farmer. \n\n== Biography ==\nBonsall was born in [[Waterville, Maine|Waterville]], [[Maine]] in the 1950s. He graduated from the [[University of Maine|University of Maine at Orono]] in 1971<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://downeast.com/land-wildlife/rare-heirloom-seeds/|title=The Maine Farmer Saving the World's Rarest Heirloom Seeds|last=Poppick|first=Laura|date=2020-03-31|website=Down East Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and moved to San Francisco and hiked across the U.S. and Mexico. He later returned to Maine to build a homestead on 85 acres in [[Industry, Maine]] called Khadighar Farm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2014/02/16/the_maine_man_who_saves_the_seeds_/|title=Maine farmer, seed curator forms new grass-roots group|last=Pols|first=Mary|date=2014-02-16|website=Portland Press Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> In 2010, he self-published a science fiction novel called \"''Through the Eyes of a Stranger (Yaro Tales)''.\" Bonsall is marred to Molly Thorkildsen and has two grown sons.\n\n== Seed saving ==\nBonsall is the founder of the Scatterseed Project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/environment/seeds-of-change-1.2769911|title=Seeds of change|last=Thompson|first=Sylvia|date=2016-08-27|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=English|first=Jean|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1986/1230/hscat.html|title=Preserving `heirloom' crops Down East|date=1986-12-30|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2020-02-11|url-status=live|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> In 2014, Bonsall founded the Grassroots Seed Network and the [[Portland Press Herald|''Portland Press Herald'']] reported: \"Nationally and even internationally, Bonsall is known as the curator of a collection of both rare and common potato varieties. The U.S. Department of Agriculture sends him potatoes it thinks might interest him. Someone in Norway might send him a few samples.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2014/02/16/the_maine_man_who_saves_the_seeds_/|title=Maine farmer, seed curator forms new grass-roots group|last=Pols|first=Mary|date=2014-02-16|website=Portland Press Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nHe is featured in the 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/seed-untold-story-932158|title='Seed: The Untold Story': Film Review|last=DeFore|first=John|date=September 23, 2016|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> documentary SEED: The Untold Story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/fighting-for-seed-diversity-documentary-seed-the-u.html|title=Fighting for Seed Diversity: Documentary SEED: The Untold Story Now Screening on PBS|last=Anna|first=Brones|date=2017-04-27|website=Paste Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenwichtime.com/local/article/Maine-farmer-and-seed-saver-speaks-at-SEED-The-11039310.php|title=Maine farmer and seed-saver speaks at film screening in Greenwich|last=Turiano|first=Jennifer|date=2017-03-31|website=GreenwichTime|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nin 2020, DownEast Magazine wrote: \"Bonsall\u2019s dispersal efforts have been so prolific that he often finds himself chasing his own tail. He\u2019ll receive what he\u2019s told is a rare variety of such-and-such, but in trying to trace it back to its original source, he\u2019ll find it came from someone who got it from someone who got it from an old hippie in western Maine.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Veganic farming ==\nBonsall is a vegan and a proponent of veganic farming, which doesn't use animal products such as manure.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glenza|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/24/vegetables-vegan-organic-agriculture-farming|title=Are vegetables vegan? The man taking aim at animal products in organic farming|date=2019-12-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/06/20/ever-heard-of-veganic-farming-neither-had-we/|title=Ever heard of veganic farming? Neither had we|last=Kamila|first=Avery Yale|date=2018-06-20|website=Portland Press Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> In 2015, [[Chelsea Green Publishing|Chelsea Green]] published ''Will Bonsall\u2019s Essential Guide to Radical, Self-reliant Gardening: Innovative Techniques for Growing Vegetables, Grains, and Perennial Food Crops with Minimal Fossil Fuel and Animal Inputs''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smallfarmcanada.ca/api/content/bb22fe8e-444c-11e9-913c-120e7ad5cf50/|title=REVIEW - A farming book with attitude|last=Wallace|first=Janet|date=2016-09-01|website=Small Farm|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> \n\nHe often writes for organic gardening publications<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherearthnews.com/organic-gardening/gardening-techniques/green-manure-ze0z1601zbay|title=Using Green Manure - Organic Gardening|last=Bonsall|first=Will|date=January 1, 2016|website=Mother Earth News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> and shares simple, vegan recipes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/food/kitchen-vignettes/will-bonsalls-succotash/|title=Will Bonsall's Succotash {{!}} Kitchen Vignettes for PBS|last=Giroux|first=Aube|date=2019-08-21|website=PBS Food|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[The Guardian]] wrote of Bonsall's farming. The article said \"Bonsall\u2019s is one of just 50 or so veganic farms in the United States, according to research by Professor Mona Seymour of Loyola Marymount University.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glenza|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/24/vegetables-vegan-organic-agriculture-farming|title=Are vegetables vegan? The man taking aim at animal products in organic farming|date=2019-12-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n* ''Will Bonsall\u2019s Essential Guide to Radical, Self-reliant Gardening: Innovative Techniques for Growing Vegetables, Grains, and Perennial Food Crops with Minimal Fossil Fuel and Animal Inputs'', 2015\n* ''Through the Eyes of a Stranger (Yaro Tales),'' 2010\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vegetarianism|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonsall, Will}}\n\n[[Category:Farmers from Maine]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Organic farmers]]\n[[Category:People from Franklin County, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Waterville, Maine]]\n[[Category:University of Maine alumni]]\n[[Category:Veganic farmers]]\n[[Category:Vegan organic gardening]]\n[[Category:Writers from Maine]]\n", "text_old": "'''Will Bonsall''' is an American author, seed saver and veganic farmer. \n\n== Biography ==\nBonsall was born in [[Waterville, Maine|Waterville]], [[Maine]] in the 1950s. He graduated from the [[University of Maine|University of Maine at Orono]] in 1971<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://downeast.com/land-wildlife/rare-heirloom-seeds/|title=The Maine Farmer Saving the World's Rarest Heirloom Seeds|last=Poppick|first=Laura|date=2020-03-31|website=Down East Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and moved to San Francisco and hiked across the U.S. and Mexico. He later returned to Maine to build a homestead on 85 acres in [[Industry, Maine]] called Khadighar Farm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2014/02/16/the_maine_man_who_saves_the_seeds_/|title=Maine farmer, seed curator forms new grass-roots group|last=Pols|first=Mary|date=2014-02-16|website=Portland Press Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> In 2010, he self-published a science fiction novel called \"''Through the Eyes of a Stranger (Yaro Tales)''.\" Bonsall is marred to Molly Thorkildsen and has two grown sons.\n\n== Seed saving ==\nBonsall is the founder of the Scatterseed Project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/environment/seeds-of-change-1.2769911|title=Seeds of change|last=Thompson|first=Sylvia|date=2016-08-27|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=English|first=Jean|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1986/1230/hscat.html|title=Preserving `heirloom' crops Down East|date=1986-12-30|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2020-02-11|url-status=live|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> In 2014, Bonsall founded the Grassroots Seed Network and the [[Portland Press Herald|''Portland Press Herald'']] reported: \"Nationally and even internationally, Bonsall is known as the curator of a collection of both rare and common potato varieties. The U.S. Department of Agriculture sends him potatoes it thinks might interest him. Someone in Norway might send him a few samples.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2014/02/16/the_maine_man_who_saves_the_seeds_/|title=Maine farmer, seed curator forms new grass-roots group|last=Pols|first=Mary|date=2014-02-16|website=Portland Press Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nHe is featured in the 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/seed-untold-story-932158|title='Seed: The Untold Story': Film Review|last=DeFore|first=John|date=September 23, 2016|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> documentary SEED: The Untold Story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/04/fighting-for-seed-diversity-documentary-seed-the-u.html|title=Fighting for Seed Diversity: Documentary SEED: The Untold Story Now Screening on PBS|last=Anna|first=Brones|date=2017-04-27|website=Paste Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenwichtime.com/local/article/Maine-farmer-and-seed-saver-speaks-at-SEED-The-11039310.php|title=Maine farmer and seed-saver speaks at film screening in Greenwich|last=Turiano|first=Jennifer|date=2017-03-31|website=GreenwichTime|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nin 2020, DownEast Magazine wrote: \"Bonsall\u2019s dispersal efforts have been so prolific that he often finds himself chasing his own tail. He\u2019ll receive what he\u2019s told is a rare variety of such-and-such, but in trying to trace it back to its original source, he\u2019ll find it came from someone who got it from someone who got it from an old hippie in western Maine.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Veganic farming ==\nBonsall is a vegan and a proponent of veganic farming, which doesn't use animal products such as manure.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glenza|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/24/vegetables-vegan-organic-agriculture-farming|title=Are vegetables vegan? The man taking aim at animal products in organic farming|date=2019-12-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/06/20/ever-heard-of-veganic-farming-neither-had-we/|title=Ever heard of veganic farming? Neither had we|last=Kamila|first=Avery Yale|date=2018-06-20|website=Portland Press Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> In 2015, [[Chelsea Green Publishing|Chelsea Green]] published ''Will Bonsall\u2019s Essential Guide to Radical, Self-reliant Gardening: Innovative Techniques for Growing Vegetables, Grains, and Perennial Food Crops with Minimal Fossil Fuel and Animal Inputs''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smallfarmcanada.ca/api/content/bb22fe8e-444c-11e9-913c-120e7ad5cf50/|title=REVIEW - A farming book with attitude|last=Wallace|first=Janet|date=2016-09-01|website=Small Farm|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> \n\nHe often writes for organic gardening publications<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherearthnews.com/organic-gardening/gardening-techniques/green-manure-ze0z1601zbay|title=Using Green Manure - Organic Gardening|last=Bonsall|first=Will|date=January 1, 2016|website=Mother Earth News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> and shares simple, vegan recipes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/food/kitchen-vignettes/will-bonsalls-succotash/|title=Will Bonsall's Succotash {{!}} Kitchen Vignettes for PBS|last=Giroux|first=Aube|date=2019-08-21|website=PBS Food|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[The Guardian]] wrote of Bonsall's farming. The article said \"Bonsall\u2019s is one of just 50 or so veganic farms in the United States, according to research by Professor Mona Seymour of Loyola Marymount University.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Glenza|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/24/vegetables-vegan-organic-agriculture-farming|title=Are vegetables vegan? The man taking aim at animal products in organic farming|date=2019-12-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n* ''Will Bonsall\u2019s Essential Guide to Radical, Self-reliant Gardening: Innovative Techniques for Growing Vegetables, Grains, and Perennial Food Crops with Minimal Fossil Fuel and Animal Inputs'', 2015\n* ''Through the Eyes of a Stranger (Yaro Tales),'' 2010\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vegetarianism|state=collapsed}}\n\